vin]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Conyers]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Michigan|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Michigan's 14th congressional district]]|years=2013\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brenda Lawrence]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Carl Levin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of United States Senators from Michigan|U.S. Senator]] from [[Michigan]]}}<br>([[Classes of United States Senators|Class 2]])|years=[[United States Senate election in Michigan, 2014|2014]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=Carl Levin}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of United States Senators from Michigan|U.S. Senator (Class 2) from Michigan]]|years=2015\u2013present|alongside=[[Debbie Stabenow]]}}\n{{s-inc|rows=2}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Claire McCaskill]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Ranking Member of the [[United States Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs|Senate Homeland Security Committee]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Shelley Moore Capito]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States Senate|United States Senators by seniority]]|years=70th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bill Cassidy]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{USSenChairs}}\n{{MI-FedRep}}\n{{U.S. Michigan Representatives}}\n{{USSenMI}}\n{{Current U.S. Senators}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 111th\u2013115th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[Michigan]]}}\n{{USCongRep/MI/111}}\n{{USCongRep/MI/112}}\n{{USCongRep/MI/113}}\n{{USCongRep/MI/114}}\n{{USCongRep/MI/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peters, Gary}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American naval officers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American naval officers]]\n[[Category:Alma College alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:Central Michigan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:Eagle Scouts]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Michigan Democrats]]\n[[Category:Michigan lawyers]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Michigan state senators]]\n[[Category:Oakland University faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Bloomfield Hills, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Sons of the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:United States Navy reservists]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Michigan]]\n[[Category:University of Detroit Mercy alumni]]\n[[Category:Wayne State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Wayne State University faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n|name          = Gary Peters\n|image         = Gary Peters official photo 115th congress.jpg\n|office        = Ranking Member of the [[United States Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs|Senate Homeland Security Committee]]\n|term_start    = January 3, 2019\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Claire McCaskill]]\n|successor     = \n|jr/sr1        = United States Senator\n|state1        = [[Michigan]]\n|alongside1    = [[Debbie Stabenow]]\n|term_start1   = January 3, 2015\n|term_end1     = \n|predecessor1  = [[Carl Levin]]\n|successor1    = \n|office2       = Member of the<br>[[U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Michigan]]\n|constituency2     = {{ushr|MI|9|9th district}} (2009\u20132013)<br>{{ushr|MI|14|14th district}} (2013\u20132015)\n|term_start2   = January 3, 2009\n|term_end2     = January 3, 2015\n|predecessor2  = [[Joe Knollenberg]]\n|successor2    = [[Brenda Lawrence]]\n|office4       = Commissioner of the [[Michigan Lottery]]\n|governor4     = [[Jennifer Granholm]]\n|term_start4   = April 9, 2003\n|term_end4     = August 7, 2007\n|predecessor4  = Jim Kipp\n|successor4    = Scott Bowen\n|state_senate5 = Michigan\n|district5     = 14th\n|term_start5   = January 3, 1995\n|term_end5     = December 31, 2002\n|predecessor5  = [[Jon Cisky]]\n|successor5    = [[Gilda Jacobs]]\n|office6 = Member of the [[Rochester Hills, Michigan|Rochester Hills City Council]]\n|term_start6 = 1991\n|term_end6 = 1993\n|birth_name    = Gary Charles Peters\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1958|12|1}}\n|birth_place   = [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse        = Colleen Ochoa\n|children      = 3\n|education     = [[Alma College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Detroit Mercy|University of Detroit]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])<br>[[Wayne State University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])<br>{{nowrap|[[Michigan State University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])}}\n|website       = {{url|peters.senate.gov|Senate website}}\n|allegiance    = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch        = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|serviceyears  = 1993\u20132000<br>2001\u20132008\n|rank          = [[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]]\n|unit          = [[Navy Supply Corps (United States)|Supply Officer]]<br>[[United States Navy Reserve]]\n|battles       = [[Operation Southern Watch]]<br/>[[War on Terror]]\n|mawards       = [[Achievement Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal]]<br>[[Military Outstanding Volunteer Service Medal]]\n}}\n'''Gary Charles Peters Sr.''' (born December 1, 1958) is an American politician serving as the [[Seniority in the United States Senate|junior]] [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] from [[Michigan]] since 2015. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he was the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|MI|14}} from 2013 to 2015. The district includes the eastern half of [[Detroit]], the [[Grosse Pointes]], [[Hamtramck]], [[Southfield, Michigan|Southfield]] and [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]]. He represented {{ushr|MI|9}} from 2009 to 2013. \n\nBefore his election to Congress, Peters served in the [[United States Navy Reserve]], spent 22 years as an investment advisor, and worked briefly in academia. He was elected to the Rochester Hills City Council in 1991 and represented the 14th District in the [[Michigan Senate]] from 1995 to 2002. He was the Democratic nominee for [[Michigan Attorney General]] in [[2002 Michigan Attorney General election|2002]], narrowly losing to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Mike Cox (U.S. politician)|Mike Cox]]. He was then appointed Commissioner of the [[Michigan Lottery]] by Governor [[Jennifer Granholm]], serving from 2003 to 2008, when he resigned to run for Congress.\n\nIn [[2014 United States Senate election in Michigan|2014]], Peters was elected to the [[United States Senate]] seat being vacated by retiring Democratic incumbent [[Carl Levin]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sen. Carl Levin won't seek reelection in 2014 \u2013 The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/sen-carl-levin-wont-seek-reelection-in-2014/2013/03/07/b66a4286-8782-11e2-9d71-f0feafdd1394_story.html |author=Rachel Weiner and Aaron Blake|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=March 7, 2013|date=March 8, 2013}}</ref> He was unopposed in the Democratic primary and defeated Republican [[Terri Lynn Land]] in the general election. He was the only non-incumbent Democrat to win a Senate election in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Schouten |first=Fredreka  |date=November 5, 2014 |title=Liberal billionaire pledges to stay in politics |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2014/11/05/tom-steyer-vows-to-stay-in-politics-despite-big-senate-losses/18550521/ |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |access-date=August 29, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/11/election-results-tom-steyer-greens-112556.html|title=Steyer, greens have rough night}}</ref>\n\nPeters is generally considered a [[New Democrats|moderate Democrat]].<ref>[https://www.ontheissues.org/senate/Gary_Peters.htm]</ref><ref>https://prospect.org/power/testing-progressives-centrist-dems-team-gop-deregulate-banks/</ref><ref>https://www.metrotimes.com/news-hits/archives/2018/05/23/thank-your-michigan-senators-bank-deregulation-is-on-its-way</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nPeters was born December 1, 1958, in [[Pontiac, Michigan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislature.mi.gov/(S(qyf4bfm3s14vpnzt1no53hm4))/documents/publications/manual/1999-2000/1999-mm-0166-0166-peters.pdf|title=Biographical sketch|accessdate= October 14, 2007|publisher=[[Michigan Legislature]] |work=Michigan Manual, 1999\u20132000 |page=166}}</ref> where he grew up. He is the son of Madeleine A. (n\u00e9e Vignier) and Herbert Garrett Peters, a historian and statistician.<ref>[http://www.mlive.com/news/detroit/index.ssf/2011/04/funeral_today_for_father_of_st.html Profile], mlive.com; accessed November 6, 2014.</ref><ref>[http://www.rochestermedia.com/lifelong-rochester-resident-and-local-historian-herb-peters-dies-at-age-95 Herb Peters dies ar age 95], rochestermedia.com; accessed November 6, 2014.</ref> His mother was a French [[war bride]] and his father was American.<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/theoaklandpress/obituary.aspx?pid=150570119 Madeleine A. Peters' obituary], legacy.com; accessed November 6, 2014.</ref> He graduated from [[Rochester High School (Michigan)|Rochester High School]] in 1976 and [[Alma College]] in 1980. He later received a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree from the [[University of Detroit]] in 1984. Peters also holds a J.D. degree from the [[Wayne State University Law School]] and an M.A. degree in philosophy from [[Michigan State University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bioguideretro.congress.gov/Home/MemberDetails?memIndex=p000595|title=Biographical Directory of the U.S. Congress - Retro Member details|website=bioguideretro.congress.gov|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\n==Military career==\nPeters joined the [[United States Navy Reserve]] in 1993 at age 34.<ref name=\"Military_Times\">{{cite news |title=Congressional Veterans Caucus Biography, Gary Peters |url=http://caucus.militarytimes.com/speaker/gary-peters/ |work=Military Times |location=Springfield, VA |access-date=June 7, 2019}}</ref>  He served for more than 10 years in units at [[Selfridge Air National Guard Base]], including [[Naval Mobile Construction Battalion 26]].<ref name=\"Military_Times\"/>  During his Navy service, Peters earned the [[Seabee combat warfare specialist insignia|Seabee Combat Warfare Specialist]] designation and carried out assignments as an [[Navy Supply Corps (United States)|assistant supply officer]].<ref name=\"Military_Times\"/>\n\nPeters' reserve duty included time in the [[Persian Gulf]] supporting [[Operation Southern Watch]], and he served overseas again during increased military activity following the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name=\"Military_Times\"/> Peters attained the rank of [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] before leaving the Reserve in 2008; his awards include the [[Achievement Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal]] and the [[Military Outstanding Volunteer Service Medal]].<ref name=\"Military_Times\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Klug |first=Fritz |date=July 26, 2014 |title=US Senate candidate Gary Peters built bridges in military, and wants to do same in upper chamber |url=https://www.mlive.com/lansing-news/2014/07/military_experience_gary_peter.html |work=MLive |location=Lansing, MI}}</ref> In 2018, he received a diploma from the [[Naval War College#College of Naval Command and Staff|College of Naval Command and Staff]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trackbill.com/legislator/us-congress-senator-gary-c-peters/623-1868/ |title=Sen. Gary C. Peters |date=2019 |website=TrackBill |publisher=TrackBill.com |location=Washington, DC}}</ref>\n\n==Business and academic career==\nPeters worked for 22 years as a financial advisor, serving as an assistant vice president at [[Merrill Lynch]] from 1980 until 1989, when he joined [[Paine Webber]] as a vice president.<ref>{{cite news|title=CONFERENCE COMMITTEE FINISHES WORK ON WALL STREET REFORM|url=http://peters.house.gov/news-releases/conference-committee-finishes-work-on-wall-street-reform/|accessdate=September 1, 2014|publisher=U.S. Representative Gary Peters|date=June 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=law>{{cite news|last1=Schlinker|first1=John|title=Gary Peters: A legal education put to many uses |url=http://www.michbar.org/journal/article.cfm?articleID=687&volumeID=53|accessdate=September 1, 2014|publisher=Michigan Bar Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rubin|first1=Jennifer|title=Could Michigan go red?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/right-turn/wp/2014/04/25/could-michigan-go-red/ |accessdate=September 1, 2014|publisher=Washington Post|date=April 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2007 to 2008, Peters served as the third Griffin Endowed Chair in American Government at [[Central Michigan University]]. In that part-time position, he taught one class a semester, plus preparing additional student activities including two policy forums, and developing a journal of Michigan politics and policy, for $65,000 a year.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gray |first=Kathleen |date=October 31, 2008 |title= Ads' harshest claims stretch the truth in Knollenberg-Peters race |url=http://www.freep.com/article/20081031/NEWS15/810310326/Ads-harshest-claims-stretch-truth-Knollenberg-Peters-race |newspaper=Detroit Free Press |location= |publisher= |accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref> Peters announced his candidacy to run for Congress two months after being hired.<ref name=Schmidt>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Peter |date=July 22, 2010 |title= At Central Michigan U., Professors Fight To Protect Their Political Ambitions |url=http://chronicle.com/article/Central-Michigan-U-Professors/123676/?sid=at |newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education |location= |publisher=|accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref> Some student and faculty members protested Peters's hiring, saying he could not be objective in the classroom while running for office and that the university job was subsidizing his campaign.<ref name=Schmidt/><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=August 8, 2007 |title= It's official: Peters will take on Knollenberg |url=http://www.freep.com/article/20070808/NEWS06/708080314/It-s-official-Peters-will-take-Knollenberg |newspaper=Detroit Free Press |location= |publisher= |accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPeters also has taught [[finance]] at Wayne State and [[strategic management]] and business [[policy]] courses at [[Oakland University]].<ref name=law/>\n\nPeters was a senior policy and financial analyst for the Michigan Department of Treasury,<ref>{{cite news |last=Weeks |first=George |date=April 10, 2003 |title=Mich. Lottery Czar Is Named; Granholm Appoints Gary Peters, Who Ran For Attorney General |newspaper=The Detroit News |location= |publisher= }}</ref> and served on arbitration panels for the [[National Association of Securities Dealers]], the [[New York Stock Exchange]] and the [[Financial Industry Regulatory Authority]].\n\n==Michigan Senate==\nPeters served on the [[Rochester Hills]] City Council from 1991 to 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=P000595|title=Profile of Gary C. Peters|website=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|publisher=U.S. Congress|accessdate=September 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sentinel-standard.com/article/20140731/News/140739805|title=Gary Peters challenges Terri Lynn Land|last1=Cook|first1=Mattie|date=July 31, 2014|accessdate=September 1, 2014|publisher=Setinel-Standard}}</ref>\n\n===Elections===\nIn November 1994, Peters was elected to the [[Michigan Senate]] to represent the [[Oakland County]]-based 14th district. He was re-elected in 1998 and served until 2002, due to the state's [[term limit]]s. Peters was succeeded in the 14th district by [[Gilda Jacobs]].\n\n===Tenure===\nThe 14th district is one of the most diverse state Senate districts\u2014containing nearly every racial, ethnic and religious group in Michigan. Located in southeastern [[Oakland County, Michigan|Oakland County]], it includes the cities of [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]], [[Bloomfield Hills, Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], [[Southfield, Michigan|Southfield]], and [[Oak Park, Michigan|Oak Park]].\n\nPeters was chosen by his Democratic colleagues to chair his party's caucus. He was also a member of the Michigan Law Revision Commission and served on the Michigan Sentencing Commission.<ref name=\"MLRC bio\"/> Both the [[Michigan State House of Representatives]] and the Senate passed a bill sponsored by Peters which banned any new wells under the state waters of the Great Lakes except in case of a state energy emergency. The bill passed into law without the signature of Governor [[John Engler]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Oakland Press |work=Local News September 1, 2006 |url=http://www.theoaklandpress.com/stories/090106/loc_2006090136.shtml |accessdate=August 9, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311055248/http://www.theoaklandpress.com/stories/090106/loc_2006090136.shtml |archivedate=March 11, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nPeters served as the [[vice chairman]] of the Senate Finance, Education, Judiciary and Economic Development Committees. He was also a member of the Natural Resources and the Mental Health and Human Services Committee.<ref name=\"MLRC bio\">\n{{cite web \n |url=http://council.legislature.mi.gov/files/mlrc/1996/biog.htm\n |title=Biographies of Commission Members and Staff \n |accessdate=October 14, 2007\n |work=Michigan Law Revision Commission Thirty-first Annual Report, 1996\n |publisher=West Publishing Company\n}}</ref>\n\n==2002 statewide elections==\n{{main|2002 Michigan Attorney General election}}\nIn his final year as a member of the Michigan Senate, Peters was a candidate for governor and later for [[Michigan Attorney General|Attorney General]]. As the Democratic nominee for attorney general, he lost in November 2002 to Republican [[Mike Cox (U.S. politician)|Mike Cox]] by about 5,200 votes \u2014less than a 0.17 percent margin.<ref>{{cite news |title =New York Times|work = National Briefing Michigan: Candidate Won't Seek Recount|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D05E0D71F39F935A15752C1A9649C8B63&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fSubjects%2fE%2fElection%20Results| accessdate=August 9, 2007 | first=David | last=Enders | date=November 26, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title =2002 Attorney General Election Results|work = U.S. Election Atlas|url=http://www.uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?fips=26&year=2002&f=0&off=9&elect=0| accessdate=August 9, 2007 }}</ref> Peters decided not to contest the election results despite reported irregularities. Several mistakes were reportedly found during analysis, including a precinct in [[Dearborn, Michigan|Dearborn]] which recorded Peters with 96 votes when he actually had 396. The race was the closest statewide contest in Michigan since the 1950 gubernatorial race.<ref>{{cite web |title =The State News|work = Peters won't request for election recount|url=http://www.statenews.com/article.phtml?pk=14251|accessdate=August 9, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n[[Michigan Governor]] [[Jennifer Granholm]] appointed Peters as the [[Michigan Lottery]] commissioner on April 9, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michigan.gov/lottery/0,4603,7-110-29196_29199---,00.html|title=Home- Michigan Lottery|website=Home- Michigan Lottery}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michigan.gov/granholm/0,4587,7-168-23442_21974-183233--,00.html|title=Former Governors \u2013 Governor Granholm Appoints Scott Bowen State Lottery Commissioner|website=www.michigan.gov}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://waddell.casinocitytimes.com/article/governor-appoints-gary-peters-as-new-state-lottery-commissioner-17531|title=Governor Appoints Gary Peters as New State Lottery Commissioner|website=waddell.casinocitytimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Garypeters.jpg|thumb|Peters during the [[112th United States Congress|112th Congress]]]]\n\n===Elections===\n;2008\n{{See also|2008 United States House of Representatives elections in Michigan#District 9}}\nOn August 7, 2007, Peters ended months of speculation by formally announcing he would run against eight-term [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] congressman [[Joe Knollenberg]] in the 9th District, which included almost all of Oakland County.  Peters resigned as state lottery commissioner to devote his full energy to the campaign.\n\nKnollenberg was considered vulnerable due to an increasing Democratic trend in what was once a classic bastion of suburban conservatism. Knollenberg's opponents in 2002 and 2004 had performed significantly below the Democratic base in the district, but he was nearly defeated in 2006 by [[Nancy Skinner (Midwestern politician)|Nancy Skinner]], a former radio talk-show host who spent virtually no money\u2013the closest a Republican had come to losing the district in almost half a century. This led the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee]] to target Knollenberg for defeat. \n\nIn the 2002 state attorney general race, Peters performed at or above the Democratic base in 72 percent of the 9th District precincts. In his 1998 state Senate campaign, he performed at or above base in 99 percent of the precincts.<ref>{{cite web |title =Swing State Project|work =9th District|url=http://www.swingstateproject.com/showDiary.do?diaryId=670|accessdate=August 9, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nPeters won the November 4 election by 33,524 votes, taking 52 percent of the vote to Knollenberg's 43 percent. [[Barack Obama]] carried Oakland County by 15 points; roughly two-thirds of Oakland County was in the 9th. Peters was the fourth person and first Democrat to represent the district since its creation in 1933<ref>{{cite web|last=Gray|first=Kathleen|title=Democratic wave helps Peters win in 9th District|url=http://www.freep.com/article/20081106/NEWS15/811060398/Democratic-wave-helps-Peters-win-9th-District|work=Detroit Free Press}}</ref> (it had previously been the 17th District from 1933 to 1953, the 18th from 1953 to 1973, the 19th from 1973 to 1983, the 18th from 1983 to 1993, the 11th from 1993 to 2003, and became the 9th in 2003).\n\n;2010\n{{see also|2010 United States House of Representatives elections in Michigan#District 9}}\nIn November 2010, Peters defeated challenges by Republican [[Andrew Raczkowski|Andrew \"Rocky\" Raczkowski]], Libertarian Adam Goodman, Independent Bob Gray, Independent Matthew Kuofie, and Green Douglas Campbell.<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = 9th District Representative in Congress 2 Year Term (1) Position Files In OAKLAND County\n |author      = State of Michigan\n |publisher   = State of Michigan\n |url         = http://miboecfr.nictusa.com/election/results/10GEN/06009000.html\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140129155056/http://miboecfr.nictusa.com/election/results/10GEN/06009000.html\n |archivedate = January 29, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{see also|2012 United States House of Representatives elections in Michigan#District 14}}\nDue to the state's population decline, as reflected by the 2010 Federal Census, Michigan lost one congressional district. As a result of the subsequent redistricting of house seats, much of Peters' 9th district, including his home in Bloomfield Hills, was merged with the [[Michigan's 12th congressional district|12th district]], represented by fellow Democrat [[Sander Levin]].  The new district retained Peters' district number\u2014the 9th\u2014but geographically was more Levin's district.\n\nIn September 2011, Peters opted to run in the newly redrawn 14th District.  The district had previously been the 13th District, represented by freshman Democrat [[Hansen Clarke]].  The redrawn district is based in Detroit, but contains a large chunk of Peters' old State Senate district and portions of his old congressional district.  Indeed, Peters had represented most of the Oakland County portion of the district at one time or another.  Due to Detroit's dwindling population, it was no longer possible to keep the district exclusively within [[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne County]].\n\nIn the August 2012 Democratic primary, Peters defeated Clarke, who had opted to follow most of his constituents into the reconfigured 14th even though his home had been drawn into the reconfigured 13th\u2014the old 14th, and Southfield Mayor [[Brenda Lawrence]].  The 14th is a heavily Democratic, 58 percent black-majority district, and Peters was overwhelmingly favored in November. As expected, he bested Republican John Hauler in the general election with 82 percent of the vote.  He was the first white congressman to represent a significant portion of Detroit since 1993.\n\n===Tenure===\nPeters was sworn into his first term in January 2009. During his time in office, he voted for the [[Recovery Act]], also known as the stimulus,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=AJ|title=Peters On Why NMTC Is Plus For Detroit|url=http://michronicleonline.com/2014/04/10/peters-on-why-nmtc-is-plus-for-detroit|accessdate=October 14, 2014|publisher=Michigan Chronicle|date=April 10, 2014}}</ref> the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Supreme Court Decision On Obamacare Inspires Reactions From Michigan Politicians|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/28/supreme-court-decision-obamacare-michigan_n_1634602.html|accessdate=October 14, 2014|publisher=Huffington Post|date=June 28, 2012}}</ref> the [[American Clean Energy and Security Act]], which would have established a national emissions trading plan, but was not passed by the full Congress,<ref>{{cite news|title=Truth Squad: Foul on ad accusing Gary Peters of supporting carbon tax|url=http://www.mlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2014/06/truth_squad_foul_on_ad_accusin.html|accessdate=October 14, 2014|publisher=MLive|date=June 10, 2014}}</ref> the [[Paycheck Fairness Act]], also not passed into law,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reinhard|first1=Beth|title=Criticized by Obama, Senate Candidate Defends Fair-Pay Stance|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2014/04/12/criticized-by-obama-senate-candidate-responds-on-fair-pay-measure/|accessdate=October 14, 2014|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=April 12, 2014}}</ref> the [[Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Helderop|first1=Brandon|title=Gary Peters inconsistent on equal pay|url=http://www.theoaklandpress.com/opinion/20140520/gary-peters-inconsistent-on-equal-pay|accessdate=October 14, 2014|publisher=Oakland Press|date=May 20, 2014}}</ref> and the [[DREAM Act]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Heinlein|first1=Gary|title=Peters tries to paint moderate image|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/elections/2014/10/09/democrat-gary-peters-aim-center/17010731/|accessdate=October 14, 2014|publisher=Detroit News|date=October 9, 2014}}</ref> to provide conditional permanent residency to certain immigrants.\n\nPeters worked with the Obama Administration to obtain debt forgiveness for [[Chrysler]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Debtholders vs. U.S. Over Chrysler Deal|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2009/04/22/debtholders-vs-us-over-chrysler-deal|work=[[New York Times]] | date=April 22, 2009}}</ref> [[House Financial Services Committee]] Chairman [[Barney Frank]] said Peters was the \"single most effective person\" in fighting against the forces that wanted to let [[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)|Detroit]] go bankrupt.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peters, principally|url=http://www2.metrotimes.com/news/story.asp?id=14714|work=Metro Times}}</ref>  In Congress, Peters opposed a plan to provide disaster relief aid, the funds for which would have come from the [[Advanced Technology Vehicles Manufacturing]] (ATVM) loan program.<ref>{{cite news|title=House Republicans Seek Auto Industry Cuts To Cover For Disaster Relief Funds|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/09/15/house-gop-seeks-cuts-to-auto-loan-program_n_964999.html|work=[[Huffington Post]] | first=Tyler|last=Kingkade|date=September 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, the ''[[Michigan Messenger]]'' wrote that Peters was \"criticizing the leadership of his own party. Peters and three other Democratic legislators ... this week formed the Spending Cuts and Deficit Reduction Working Group and proposed a series of bills to cut spending. Peters\u2019 bill makes cuts in the federal energy budget.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Peters criticizes Dem. leadership on spending|url=http://michiganmessenger.com/39931/peters-criticizes-dem-leadership-on-spending|work=The Michigan Messenger|publisher=[[The American Independent News Network]]|accessdate=April 4, 2012}}</ref> \"We have been growing increasingly frustrated with the lack of action and talking about specifics and putting those on the table,\" Peters said. \"We\u2019ve been frustrated with both Democratic leadership and Republicans.\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Simmi|last=Aujla|title=Four House Democrats revolt|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0710/39950.html|publisher=[[Politico]]|accessdate=April 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPeters allied himself with the [[Occupy Wall Street]] movement, making an appearance at [[Occupy Detroit]] on November 6, 2011. Speaking to reporters, he said: \"It's speculation on [[Wall Street]] that we're still paying the price for here, particularly in Detroit that almost brought the auto industry to a collapse because of what we saw on Wall Street. So we put in restrictions, or put in regulations necessary to reign that in, and right now in Washington I\u2019m facing a Republican majority that wants to undo that.\"<ref name=\"Fisher 2011\">{{cite web|last=Fisher |first=Beth|title=Occupy Detroit Gets Union Support |url=http://detroit.cbslocal.com/2011/11/06/233330/ |work= [[CBS Detroit]]|accessdate=November 21, 2011|date=November 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Peters was one of 118 house Democrats who signed a letter to the president urging him to support the [[United Nations Population Fund]] (UNFPA), a multinational organization that provides health services (including birth control) to women, children and families in over 150 countries.<ref name=\" Joe Crowley,2011\">{{cite web|last=|first=|title=Over 100 Democrats Join Reps. Crowley, Maloney, Lowey and Berman in Call for Continued Support of UNFPA\n|url= http://crowley.house.gov/press-release/over-100-democrats-join-reps-crowley-maloney-lowey-and-berman-call-continued-support|work= Joseph Crowley|accessdate=November 21, 2011|date=November 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Peters voiced opposition to a Michigan law which prohibits insurers from offering abortion coverage as a standard feature in health plans.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Woods|first1=Ashley|title=Michigan's 'Rape Insurance' Abortion Rider Law Goes Into Effect Today|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/03/13/michigans-abortion-rider-_n_4958517.html|website=www.huffingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nAs a Representative, Peters sponsored 37 bills, including:<ref>{{cite web|title=Representative Peters's Legislation|url=https://www.congress.gov/member/gary-peters/1929?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22Gary+Peters%22%5D%2C%22sponsorship%22%3A%22sponsored%22%2C%22type%22%3A%22bills%22%2C%22congress%22%3A%22all%22%7D|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=January 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====111th Congress (2009\u20132010)====\n* H.R. 1500, a bill to expand and make refundable the [[Child and Dependent Care Credit]], introduced March 12, 2009\n* H.R. 1527, a bill to impose a 60% income tax on bonuses exceeding $10,000 paid to employees of businesses in which the federal government has at least 79% ownership of, introduced March 16, 2009\n* H.R. 1957, a bill to replace the Hope Scholarship and Lifetime Learning tax credits and the tax deduction for tuition expenses with an income tax credit equal to 50% of tuition and related expenses, up to $10,000 per taxable year, introduced April 2, 2009\n* H.R. 3246, a bill to create and expand programs for developing and improving vehicle technology, introduced July 17, 2009, reintroduced in the 112th Congress as H.R. 1367 and in the 113th Congress as H.R. 1027\n* H.R. 5302, a bill to establish a program to increase access to capital for small businesses, introduced May 13, 2009\n* H.R. 5337, a bill to make it a crime to create, sell, distribute, or offer material containing extreme animal cruelty, which the bill defines, introduced May 18, 2010\n* H.R. 5780, a bill to eliminate tax credits and deductions for oil and natural gas, introduced July 20, 2010\n\n====112th Congress (2011\u20132012)====\n* H.R. 3233, a bill to exclude the value of vehicles used for transportation from the resource limit in the [[Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program]], introduced October 14, 2011\n* H.R. 6078, a bill to increase government-wide prime contract award goals for small businesses and to increase percentage goals for historically underutilized business zones, and small businesses owned and controlled by socially and economically disadvantaged individuals, introduced June 29, 2012\n\n====113th Congress (2013\u20132014)====\n* H.R. 4057, a bill to allow for the construction of [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] customs plazas at land ports of entry into the United States, with priority given to those that experience greater traffic, introduced February 11, 2014\n* H.R. 4244, a bill to expand the small employer health insurance tax credits from businesses with 25 employees to 50, to increase the maximum allowance of such credit, to eliminate the requirement that employers contribute the same percentage to health insurance as employees, and to eliminate the cap limiting employer contributions to average premiums in the health insurance exchanges, introduced March 13, 2014\n* H.R. 4941, a bill to designate up to 20 areas as \"Promise Zones\" and to have these zones receive priority consideration in federal grant programs and initiatives, introduced June 23, 2014\n* H.R. 5045, 5046, 5047, and 5048, a package of veteran bills, introduced July 9, 2014. H.R. 5045 would prohibit the [[Small Business Administration]] (SBA) from imposing a guarantee fee on loans from SBA. H.R. 5046 would encourage the development of regulations to protect the financial security of veterans. H.R. 5047 would prohibit the Secretary of Veteran Affairs from altering the accessibility of any veteran's health care based on when he or she last received care from a veteran health care facility. H.R. 5048 would extend, create, and study various programs to reduce the suicide rate among veterans.\n\n===Committee assignments===\n\n*[[Committee on Commerce, Science, and Transportation]]\n**[[United States Senate Commerce Subcommittee on Aviation Operations, Safety, and Security|Subcommittee on Aviation Operations, Safety, and Security]]\n**[[United States Senate Commerce Subcommittee on Communications, Technology, and the Internet|Subcommittee on Communications, Technology, Innovation, and the Internet]]\n**[[United States Senate Commerce Subcommittee on Oceans, Atmosphere, Fisheries, and Coast Guard|Subcommittee on Oceans, Atmosphere, Fisheries, and Coast Guard]]\n**[[United States Senate Commerce Subcommittee on Science and Space|Subcommittee on Space, Science and Competitiveness]]\n*[[United States Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs|Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs]] (Ranking Member)\n**Subcommittee on Federal Spending Oversight and Emergency Management \n*[[United States Congress Joint Economic Committee|Joint Economic Committee]]\n\n;Leadership\nPeters was named senior whip for the Democratic caucus in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Spangler|first=Todd|title=Gary Peters nabs senior whip position in Congress|url=http://www.freep.com/article/20130109/NEWS15/130109044/U-S-Rep-Gary-Peters-senior-whip-Congress|accessdate=April 25, 2014|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n{{Expand section|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn the Bipartisan Index created by [[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]] and the [[McCourt School of Public Policy]] that ranks members of the United States Congress by their degree of bipartisanship (by measuring the frequency each member's bills attract co-sponsors from the opposite party and each member's co-sponsorship of bills by members of the opposite party), Peters was ranked as the 32nd most bipartisan member of the U.S. Senate during the [[114th United States Congress|114th U.S. Congress]], and the 17th most bipartisan member (and the 4th most bipartisan Democrat in the U.S. Senate) during the [[115th United States Congress|115th U.S. Congress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20Senate%20Scores.pdf |title=The Lugar Center \u2013 McCourt School Bipartisan Index \u2013 Senate|publisher=[[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]]|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/Senate%20Scores%20115th%20Congress%20Full.pdf|title=The Lugar Center \u2013 McCourt School Bipartisan Index \u2013 Senate|publisher=[[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]]|date=March 19, 2019|access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Israel ===\nIn March 2017, Peters co-sponsored the [[Israel Anti-Boycott Act]] (S. 720), which made it a federal crime for Americans to encourage or participate in boycotts against Israel and [[Israeli settlement]]s in the occupied [[Israeli-occupied territories|Palestinian territories]] if protesting actions by the Israeli government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/senate-bill/720/cosponsors|title=Cosponsors - S.720 - 115th Congress (2017-2018): Israel Anti-Boycott Act|date=23 March 2017|website=www.congress.gov}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2017/07/senate-bill-would-make-it-a-federal-crime-to-boycott-israel.html|title=43 Senators Want to Make It a Federal Crime to Boycott Israeli Settlements|last=Levitz|first=Eric|date=2017-07-19|website=Intelligencer|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== China ===\nIn November 2017, in response to efforts by [[China]] to purchase tech companies based in the US, Peters was one of nine senators to cosponsor a bill that would broaden the federal government's ability to prevent foreign purchases of U.S. firms through increasing the strength of the [[Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States]] (CFIUS). The scope of the CFIUS would be expanded to allow it to review along with possibly decline smaller investments and add additional national security factors for CFIUS to consider including if information about Americans would be exposed as part of transactions or whether the deal would facilitate fraud.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-regulation-m-a/u-s-lawmakers-introduce-bipartisan-bills-on-foreign-investment-amid-china-worries-idUSKBN1D8267|title=U.S. lawmakers introduce bipartisan bills on foreign investment amid China worries|first=Diane|last=Bartz|date=November 8, 2017|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\n===Guns===\nPeters is a [[gun]] owner.<ref name=\"Lawler1004G\">{{cite web|last1=Lawler|first1=Emily|title=Gary Peters, Mark Totten talk guns and world peace at MLive Ballot Bash in Royal Oak|url=http://www.mlive.com/lansing-news/index.ssf/2014/10/royal_oak_ballot_bash_includes.html|website=MLive.com|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> As of 2010, Peters had a \"D\" rating from the [[National Rifle Association]].<ref name=\"VS1004G\">{{cite web|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|url=https://votesmart.org/interest-group/1130/rating/5566|website=Vote Smart|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]], Peters participated in the [[Chris Murphy gun control filibuster]].<ref name=\"Facher1004G\">{{cite web|last1=Facher|first1=Lev|title=U.S. Sen. Gary Peters participates in Senate filibuster over gun control|url=http://michiganradio.org/post/us-sen-gary-peters-participates-senate-filibuster-over-gun-control|website=Michigan Radio|accessdate=October 4, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Peters was one of forty senators to introduce the Background Check Expansion Act, a bill that would require background checks for the sale or transfer of all firearms. Exceptions to the bill's background check requirement included transfers between members of law enforcement, loaning firearms for either hunting or sporting events on a temporary basis, providing firearms as gifts to members of one's immediate family, firearms being transferred as part of an inheritance, or giving a firearm to another person temporarily for immediate self-defense.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://urbanmilwaukee.com/pressrelease/u-s-senator-tammy-baldwin-helps-introduce-background-check-expansion-act-to-reduce-gun-violence/|title=U.S. Senator Tammy Baldwin Helps Introduce Background Check Expansion Act To Reduce Gun Violence|date=January 9, 2019|publisher=urbanmilwaukee.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.michiganradio.org/post/sen-peters-gun-control-net-neutrality-and-new-banking-regulations|title=Sen. Peters on gun control, net neutrality, and new banking regulations|last=Staff|first=Lara Moehlman, Stateside|website=www.michiganradio.org|language=en|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. Senate==\n\n===Elections===\n;2014\n{{Main|2014 United States Senate election in Michigan}}\nIn 2014, Peters ran for the [[United States Senate|Senate]] seat being vacated by retiring Senator [[Carl Levin]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Democrat Gary Peters says he wants to continue Carl Levin's legacy in US Senate|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/index.ssf/2013/05/gary_peters.html|publisher=MLive|author=Fritz Klug|accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref> Peters was endorsed by Levin and Senator [[Debbie Stabenow]], and his entrance largely cleared the field of potential Democratic challengers.<ref name=Klug>{{cite news|last=Klug|first=Fritz|title=U.S. Senators Carl Levin, Debbie Stabenow endorse Gary Peters in 2014 U.S. Senate election|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/index.ssf/2013/05/us_senators_carl_levin_debbie.html|accessdate=April 9, 2014|newspaper=MLive|date=May 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nPeters' largest independent supporter was the Senate Majority PAC, which spent almost $3.2 million for ads attacking Peters' opponent in the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/home/terri-lynn-land-super-pac-target|title=Terri Lynn Land Targeted in Super PAC Ad in Michigan|date=July 12, 2014|website=Roll Call}}</ref><ref>http://www.senatemajority.com/2014/03/news/senate-majority-pac-launches-new-ads-in-michigan-and-arkansas</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/03/senate-majority-pac-arkansas-michigan-105138.html|title=Senate Majority PAC up in Ark., Mich.|publisher=}}</ref><ref>http://fec.gov/data/IndependentExpenditure.do?format=html&id=ieNational&election_yr=2014&candidateOfficeState=MI&candOffice=S</ref> In July 2014, Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] supported Peters at a campaign fundraising event.<ref>{{cite news|last1=LeBlanc|first1=Steve|title=Elizabeth Warren Hits The Campaign Trail For Fellow Democrats|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/07/13/elizabeth-warren-democrats_n_5581603.html|accessdate=October 14, 2014|publisher=Huffington Post|date=July 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhile the campaign was considered competitive early on, various missteps by the campaign of his [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] opponent [[Terri Lynn Land]] and her reluctance to appear in public benefited the Peters campaign; he had consistent leads in polls late in the campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/meet-gop-senate-candidate-republicans-love-hate/story?id=26224000|title=Meet the Republican Even the GOP Hates|first=A. B. C.|last=News|date=October 17, 2014|website=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/senate-update-the-swing-states-that-never-swung/|title=Senate Update: The Swing States That Never Swung|date=October 28, 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/home/senate-races-2014-why-michigan-never-became-iowa|title=Senate Races 2014: Why Michigan Never Became Iowa|date=October 22, 2014|newspaper=Roll Call|last1=Levinson|first1=Alexis|last2=Levinson|first2=Alexis}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n{{Update|section|2=[[115th Congress]]|date=January 2019}}\n*[[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.armed-services.senate.gov/|title=Home \u2013 United States Committee on Armed Services|author=|date=|website=www.armed-services.senate.gov}}</ref>\n**[[United States Senate Armed Services Subcommittee on Airland|Subcommittee on Airland]]<ref name=\"armed-services.senate.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.armed-services.senate.gov/about/subcommittees|title=Subcommittees \u2013 United States Committee on Armed Services|author=|date=|website=www.armed-services.senate.gov}}</ref>\n**[[United States Senate Armed Services Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities|Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities]]<ref name=\"armed-services.senate.gov\"/>\n**[[United States Senate Armed Services Subcommittee on Strategic Forces|Subcommittee on Strategic Forces]]<ref name=\"armed-services.senate.gov\"/>\n*[[Committee on Commerce, Science, and Transportation]]\n**[[United States Senate Commerce Subcommittee on Surface Transportation and Merchant Marine Infrastructure, Safety, and Security|Subcommittee on Surface Transportation and Merchant Marine Infrastructure]] (Ranking Member)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.commerce.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/surfacetransportationandmerchantmarineinfrastructuresafetyandsecurity|title=U.S. Senate Committee On Commerce, Science, & Transportation \u2013 Surface Transportation and Merchant Marine Infrastructure, Safety and Security|work=U.S. Senate Committee On Commerce, Science, & Transportation|access-date=2018-08-13|language=en}}</ref>\n**[[United States Senate Commerce Subcommittee on Aviation Operations, Safety, and Security|Subcommittee on Aviation Operations, Safety, and Security]]\n**[[United States Senate Commerce Subcommittee on Communications, Technology, and the Internet|Subcommittee on Communications, Technology, Innovation, and the Internet]]\n**[[United States Senate Commerce Subcommittee on Oceans, Atmosphere, Fisheries, and Coast Guard|Subcommittee on Oceans, Atmosphere, Fisheries, and Coast Guard]]\n**[[United States Senate Commerce Subcommittee on Science and Space|Subcommittee on Space, Science and Competitiveness]]\n*[[United States Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs|Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs]] (Ranking Member)\n**[[United States Senate Homeland Security Subcommittee on Federal Spending Oversight and Emergency Management|Subcommittee on Federal Spending Oversight and Emergency Management]] (Ranking Member)<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.hsgac.senate.gov/subcommittees/fso/about |title = About Subcommittee on Federal Spending Oversight and Emergency Management (FSO) &#124; Homeland Security & Governmental Affairs Committee}}</ref>\n**[[United States Senate Homeland Security Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations|Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations]] \n*[[United States Congress Joint Economic Committee|Joint Economic Committee]]\n\nSource:<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Peters: Committee Assignments |url=https://www.peters.senate.gov/about/committee-assignments}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPeters is married to Colleen Ochoa from Waterford; they have three children. They reside in [[Bloomfield Hills]].<ref>{{cite web |title =The Michigan Bar Journal| work =Gary Peters: A legal education put to many uses|url=http://www.michbar.org/journal/article.cfm?articleID=687&volumeID=53|accessdate=August 9, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to financial disclosure documents, Peters had assets of between approximately $1.7 million and $6.3 million at the end of 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/otherdata.php?cycle=2016&cid=N00029277&type=I|title=Sen. Gary Peters: Campaign Finance/Money \u2013 Other Data \u2013 Senator 2016 {{!}} OpenSecrets|website=www.opensecrets.org|access-date=January 8, 2017}}</ref> In 2014, Peters' net worth ranked 37th in the Senate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/pfds/summary.php?year=2014&cid=N00029277|title=Gary Peters (D-Mich), 2014 {{!}} OpenSecrets|website=www.opensecrets.org|access-date=January 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPeters received the [[Distinguished Eagle Scout Award]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.peters.senate.gov/about/meet-gary|title=About Gary|publisher=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPeters is a member of the [[Sons of the American Revolution]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://missar.org/PDF/WMM%20Dec%2010.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=October 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304063956/http://missar.org/PDF/WMM%20Dec%2010.pdf |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  His ancestor William Garrett served in the [[Virginia Militia]] in the Revolutionary War alongside General Washington at Valley Forge during the harsh winter of 1777-1778.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/lansing-news/index.ssf/2014/07/military_experience_gary_peter.html|title=US Senate candidate Gary Peters built bridges in military, and wants to do same in upper chamber|publisher=|date=July 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peters.senate.gov/newsroom/press-releases/peters-delivers-president-george-washingtons-farewell-address-on-senate-floor|title=Peters Delivers President George Washington\u2019s Farewell Address on Senate Floor {{!}} U.S. Senator Gary Peters of Michigan|website=www.peters.senate.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Main|Electoral history of Gary Peters}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n{{commonscat|Gary Peters}}\n*[https://peters.senate.gov/ U.S. Senator Gary Peters] official U.S. Senate site\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141220085601/http://www.petersformichigan.com/ Gary Peters for U.S. Senate]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Michigan/Government/Federal/US_Senate/Gary_Peters_%5BD%5D|Gary Peters}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=P000595 | votesmart=8749 | fec=S4MI00355 | congress=gary-peters/P000595 }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://ballotpedia.org/Gary_Peters Biography] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/412305 Congressional profile] at [[GovTrack]]\n* [http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/412305 Congressional profile] at [[Participatory Politics Foundation|OpenCongress]]\n* [http://www.rollcall.com/members/29032.html Congressional profile] at ''[[Roll Call]]''\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00029277 Financial information (federal office)] at [[Center for Responsive Politics|OpenSecrets.org]]\n* [https://apps.washingtonpost.com/politics/capitol-assets/member/gary-peters Financial investments (personal)] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* [http://www.legistorm.com/member/958/Rep_Gary_Peters.html Staff salaries, trips and personal finance] at LegiStorm.com\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/MI/Gary_Peters.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* [http:/