{"title_page": "Age of Empires Online", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = Age of Empires Online\n|image = Age of Empire Online cover.jpg\n|caption =\n|developer = [[Robot Entertainment]]<br />[[Gas Powered Games]]\n|publisher = [[Microsoft Game Studios]]\n|designer =\n|series = ''[[Age of Empires]]''\n|engine = \n|platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n|released = {{Video game release|WW|August 16, 2011<ref name=\"ignrelease\">{{cite web|url=http://pc.ign.com/articles/117/1171807p1.html|title=Age of Empires Online Release Date|website=IGN|date=May 31, 2011|accessdate=September 30, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826023057/http://pc.ign.com/articles/117/1171807p1.html|archive-date=August 26, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>}}\n|genre = [[Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy game]]\n|modes = [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n}}\n'''''Age of Empires Online''''' was a [[multiplayer online real-time strategy game]] developed by [[Robot Entertainment]] and [[Gas Powered Games]], which released on August 16, 2011.<ref name=\"ignrelease\" /> Based upon the gameplay of the ''[[Age of Empires]]'' series, it was originally developed by [[Robot Entertainment]], but on February 24, 2011, [[Gas Powered Games]], took over production. The game was published by [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/press/2010/aug10/08-16msgamescompcpr.aspx|title=Microsoft Heralds a New Age of Gaming With \"Age of Empires Online\"|publisher=Microsoft website|date=August 16, 2010|accessdate=September 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120621112909/http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/press/2010/aug10/08-16MSGamescomPCPR.aspx|archive-date=June 21, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe game was [[free-to-play]]\u2014it was free for users to play, though premium content could be earned or purchased, such as access to special items and blueprints, and more quests and features.\n\nOn March 27, 2012, the game premiered on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] after a major overhaul patch which addressed complaints of an \"MMO-like grind\" and many other features, along with the debut of the [[Celts|Celtic]] civilization. On June 15, 2012 the premium content system was changed to offer the option to purchase all past and future content through \"Empire points\" earned in game, or by purchasing the points directly with real world money.\n\n{{As of|2013|1|3}}, [[Microsoft]] ceased further development on the game. A Microsoft representative later announced on the forums that on August 22, 2013, the [[Games for Windows \u2013 Live]] Marketplace would be shut down, leaving the game only accessible by current or former players.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forums.ageofempiresonline.com/forums/1/371493/ShowThread.aspx|title=Error|work=ageofempiresonline.com|access-date=August 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827132206/http://forums.ageofempiresonline.com/forums/1/371493/ShowThread.aspx|archive-date=August 27, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In September 2013, it was announced that the game would remain functional until July 1, 2014 when the service would be shut down.<ref>{{cite web|title=Age of Empires Online Shutdown Confirmed, Detailed|url=https://www.trueachievements.com/n14728/age-of-empires-online-shutdown-confirmed-detailed|website=True Achievements|access-date=August 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818215923/https://www.trueachievements.com/n14728/age-of-empires-online-shutdown-confirmed-detailed|archive-date=August 18, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The closure was due to the content being too expensive to maintain.<ref name=shut>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2013/8/19/4635640/age-of-empires-online-failure-to-be-profitable-due-to-its-lack-of|title=Age of Empires Online's lack of new content drove revenue loss|author=Corriea, Alexa Ray|website=Polygon|date=Aug 19, 2013|access-date=January 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612162928/https://www.polygon.com/2013/8/19/4635640/age-of-empires-online-failure-to-be-profitable-due-to-its-lack-of|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, ''Age of Empires Online'' was reestablished using Microsoft's publicly released developer-kit for the game and is now hosted on a [[server emulator]] known as ''Project Celeste''. The game can be played for free in single-player and multiplayer mode with all online features fully enabled.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://projectceleste.com/|title=Age of Empires Online \u2013 Celeste Fan Project|website=Age of Empires Online \u2013 Celeste Fan Project|language=en|access-date=2019-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930070719/https://www.projectceleste.com/|archive-date=September 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In May 2019, the team announced that they are developing Microsoft's unreleased Roman civilization for play based upon all known data of the civilization before the official servers were closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forums.projectceleste.com/threads/roman-civilization-announcement.4056/|title=Roman Civilization Announcement|website=Age Of Empires Online -- Celeste Fan Project}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Age of Empires Online Screenshot - Battle.png|thumb|left|300px|Gameplay screenshot showing a battle scene.]]\n''Age of Empires Online'', like its predecessors, is a real-time based strategy videogame. The game features much of the gameplay of [[Age of Empires|the series]], with the addition of a [[massively multiplayer online game|massive multiplayer online gaming]] element. The player possesses a capital city for each started civilization, that continues to exist when the player is offline. Also, the game features a great quantity of new content, such as the ability to craft items with earned materials and trading with other players.<ref name=\"features\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/features|title=General Features|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|accessdate=September 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920171542/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/features|archive-date=September 20, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe main gameplay revolved around the player developing a civilization from its birth to its peak and fall. To assure victory, the player had to gather and preserve resources to spend on new units, buildings and more advanced technology.\n\nCivilian units, called ''villagers'', were used to gather resources (hunting, fishing, farming, forestry, mining etc.).. Resources could be traded, and also \"spent\" to train units, construct buildings, and research technologies.\n\n===Units===\n''Age of Empires Online'' includes five classes of military units: Infantry, archers, cavalry, [[siege]] weaponry, and [[navy|naval]] units. All military classes are developed to maintain a balance on gameplay, and thus avoiding visible advantages between civilizations. As an example, a unit powerful against buildings can be weak against a certain kind of cavalry. Unique units are available for the Greek, Egyptian, Celts, and Persian civilizations, either from the start of the game or through advisor cards. These civilization-specific units are generally more powerful, but can still be vulnerable to certain units. The [[priest]] is a special kind of military unit that has the ability to convert enemy units to the player's civilization, and to heal allied units.<ref name=\"ageofempiresonline\">{{cite web |url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/features |title=Features |publisher=Age of Empires Online |accessdate=October 19, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018141503/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/features |archive-date=October 18, 2012 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nEvery player has a limit to the total number of units they can create\u2014a population limit\u2014but may not immediately use the entire potential population. The population limit increases with the number of houses or town centers in the player's village to a maximum of 200, with each house contributing five (or ten for the Norse) and each town center contributing 20 to the limit. There are two important features for unit management: The idle villager button, which helps players identify villagers that have not been assigned a task, and the town bell, which sends all of the player's villagers into the nearest town center, fortress or tower for safety.<ref name=\"ageofempiresonline\" />\n\n===Buildings===\nThe buildings in ''Age of Empires Online'' are either economic or military buildings. Buildings can research technologies and upgrades that increase economic, military or unit-based efficiency, as well as provide resources for the player. Each civilization has unique buildings, but some are common for all civilizations; the most important of these being the town center, where villagers are created, resources are stored, some technologies researched and in which the player can advance to the next age. The town center can fire arrows at enemy units within range. Other economic buildings available include the storehouse for resources, farms, docks (the dock may also produce several military ships), and houses to support a higher population.\n\nMilitary buildings include unit-producing buildings such as [[barracks]], archery ranges, stables, and fortresses, as well as defensive buildings such as walls and towers. Military buildings can perform research to improve the abilities of military units, increasing their strength, defensive capabilities, or other attributes. The fortress is a powerful defensive building which can train a variety of units, including the civilization's unique units, and fires arrows at enemy units within range. It can only be built after a player has reached the third age. There are two other important defensive buildings: Walls and towers. Walls are used to prevent access for enemy units to an enclosed area, while friendly units can traverse the walls through inserted gates. Towers are equipped with the ability to fire arrows at enemy units, or garrison friendly units for protection, and can be used in conjunction with walls in establishing defense lines. Watch posts are used for extendings the line of sight.\n\n===Capital city===\nThe capital city is similar to the \"Home city\" concept implemented in ''[[Age of Empires III]]''. The city functions as the player's home base for their civilization. It continues to exist even when the player logs out of the game, though it cannot be attacked or altered by other players. Through the capital city, the player can manage quests, improve technologies, send mail, craft items, participate in player to player trade, acquire and equip new gear for individual units, and visit other player's cities. Stores built within the city can be visited by other players and currency used for the items purchased will add to the player's funds. Unlike the home city from ''Age of Empires III'' where you can only customize the look of buildings, the capital city is completely customizable; buildings and rewards can be placed anywhere on the city map as the player chooses. Players can add buildings, rewards, houses as well as statues and bushes along with other things to decorate their capital city. \"Vanity Island\" exist to add new bushes and statues for the player to use to decorate their capital city. The city is also used as a gateway to other AI controlled cities within the region, where a player can visit and acquire new quests and items. The capital city also has many different buildings that the player can build. Craft schools, built from the city, produce gear and consumables for the player to use. Additionally, Microsoft released a crafting app for [[Windows Phone]] which a player can use to assist in crafting within the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.windowsphone.com/en-us/store/app/crafting-guide/bf135187-f944-4947-bf36-f94b8d46f6e4 |title=Crafting Guide &#124; Windows Phone Apps+Games Store (United States) |publisher=Windowsphone.com |accessdate=January 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111005149/http://www.windowsphone.com/en-us/store/app/crafting-guide/bf135187-f944-4947-bf36-f94b8d46f6e4 |archive-date=November 11, 2012 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Quests===\nQuests are the main [[PvE]] aspect of the game. Quests generally involve fighting and defeating the AI player. They are similar to the campaigns in previous ''[[Age of Empires]]'' games. They are completed when the objectives are met. Objectives in quests vary greatly, some quests involve defeating enemies, others involve protecting a building or unit, and some involve collecting a certain amount of resources while defending from the enemy. Quest rewards include experience points, gold, empire points, chests, and sometimes gear.  Certain quests also have a co-op option, which allows the player to do the quest with another player to help them. Certain quests also have an \"elite\" version, which allows for the player to gain a greater amount of rewards, but is more difficult presenting the player with a greater challenge.\n\nThe different civilizations also have different quest lines, e.g. the Celts have 80 unique quests that the other civilizations do not possess.<ref name=\"SpringPatchNotes\">{{cite web|url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120327|title=Blog post: Spring Patch notes|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|date=March 27, 2012|accessdate=September 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116155857/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120327|archive-date=November 16, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===PvP===\nPlayer versus player, or [[Player versus player|PvP]], is another aspect of the game. PvP in this game can be started in one of two ways: By using Sparta PvP to find a random match, or by using the arena in the capital city to play against a party member. Sparta PvP can be accessed by visiting the Sparta region in the world map. In Sparta PvP, there are two different types of PvP options. Standard PvP is the first option and allows the player to use star techs from their tech-tree as well as any gear and advisors that they have equipped in their capital city. This PvP option was first to be released. Champion mode PvP is the second Sparta PvP option. This is also sometimes known as ranked PvP while Standard PvP is known as unranked PvP. In this PvP option all gears, star techs and advisors are disabled and cannot be used to start the players off at an even footing. All gears equipped will provide the units with a cosmetic change but will not affect their stats like they would normally do in PvE missions.<ref name=\"features\" />\n\nIn Sparta PvP, the player starts off with a minimal amount of resources, a few villagers and their scout. Map selection is random and cannot be chosen by either players. Champion mode PvP results will also determine your [[TrueSkill]] ranking which is used to determine a player's rank globally as well as to help find the player a match and opponents for PvP. Currently, in Sparta PvP, there is an option for 1v1 PvP and 2v2 PvP. Rewards from Sparta PvP include experience points, empire points, gold and Sparta points which can be used in the stores in Sparta for chests, gear and consumables.\n\nPvP is also accessible through the Arena in the player's capital city. While identical to Sparta PvP in many ways, Arena PvP can differ in many ways. In Arena PvP, you can play against any human opponent in your party as well as choose the map and teams (if it is a 2v2 match) before starting the game. Arena PvP  will not affect your Sparta PvP Trueskill ranking. Finally, arena PvP also does not provide any rewards to the winning player. The August 2012 update also added a new spectator mode option for Arena PvP<ref name=\"AnniversaryUpdate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120814-2|title=Blog post: Anniversary Update - Design Notes|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|date=August 14, 2012|accessdate=September 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817225606/http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120814-2|archive-date=August 17, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the October 2012 update made Arena PvP (Standard or Champion mode) free for all players.<ref name=\"ageofempiresonline2\">{{cite web |author=GPG Design Team |url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20121022 |title=Blog |publisher=Age of Empires Online |date=October 22, 2012 |accessdate=January 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024231553/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20121022 |archive-date=October 24, 2012 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Civilizations===\nSix [[civilization]]s are available. Premium civilizations start at level 1 and are the Greeks, Egyptians, and Celts. Pro civilizations start at level 20 and are the Persians, Babylonians and the Norse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/civilizations|title=Civilizations|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|accessdate=September 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921002447/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/civilizations|archive-date=September 21, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Each civilization has technologies and units that are unique to them, so that no civilization possesses all the technologies or units possible within the game.\n\n==Development==\n[[File:AoEO-comparison1.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The developers intended for the game to be reminiscent of the previous games from the series, yet have a \"bold and more graphic look with a lot of character\".<ref name=\"Artdesign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.robotentertainment.com/blog/detail/Vision-behind-Age-Empires-Online|title=The Vision behind Age of Empires Online|publisher=[[Robot Entertainment]]|date=September 3, 2010|accessdate=April 27, 2012|last=Kubalak|first=David|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221011536/http://robotentertainment.com/blog/detail/Vision-behind-Age-Empires-Online|archive-date=February 21, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Note the near identical units and building placement.]]\n''Age of Empires Online'', under the working title ''Project S'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5582009/ex+age-of-empires-devs-working-on-microsoft-strategy-game |title=Ex-Age of Empires Devs Working On Microsoft StrategyGame |publisher=Kotaku |first=Luke |last=Plunkett |date=July 7, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818072443/http://kotaku.com/5582009/ex%2Bage-of-empires-devs-working-on-microsoft-strategy-game |archivedate=August 18, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> was to be the first game [[game development|developed]] by [[Robot Entertainment]], a company founded by 45 of the 110 former staff members of [[Ensemble Studios]], who created the ''[[Age of Empires]]'' series.<ref name=\"Robot\" /> The game was officially announced on August 16, 2010. Robot was hired by Microsoft to develop the game over a 24-month period. The entire studio team focused on it as their sole project, in an effort to earn startup funds for Robot's future projects.<ref name=\"Robot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/04/18/interview-patrick-hudson-robot-entertainment.aspx|title=Director's Cut: Interview With Robot Entertainment's Patrick Hudson|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=April 18, 2012|accessdate=April 30, 2012|first=Matt|last=Helgeson|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422063546/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/04/18/interview-patrick-hudson-robot-entertainment.aspx|archive-date=April 22, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring early production, ''Age of Empires Online'' was originally called ''Age of Empires IV''. The development team had noticed that many other RTS game developers had moved away from the \"economic game\". The team felt that ''[[Age of Empires II: The Age of Kings]]'' had blended the economic and military aspects of the game perfectly, so they decided to play test it with hindsight. They noticed that many features had been lost or changed over time. It was during this time the team decided to do an \"''Age of Kings'' style gameplay in an ''[[Age of Empires (video game)|Age of Empires]]'' setting\". The designers were surprised that fans of the series were most fond of the simpler aspects of the previous titles. Former ''Age of Empires II'' lead designer Ian M. Fischer stated, \"When we started floating some of the early [AoEO] out to people other pieces fell into place \u2013 I cannot tell you how many times I have had someone email me or talk to me at a show and mention how much they loved the villagers carrying big hunks of meat in the original Age or the priest \"wololo\"\". From that point on, one of the goals was to invoke nostalgia from fans of the series when playing the game, despite the newer and updated features.<ref name=\"Earlydesign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.robotentertainment.com/blog/detail/Hi-Honey-Were-Home|title=Hi Honey, We're Home|publisher=[[Robot Entertainment]]|date=August 27, 2010|accessdate=April 27, 2012|last=Fischer|first=Ian M.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301120444/http://www.robotentertainment.com/blog/detail/Hi-Honey-Were-Home|archive-date=March 1, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe decision to make the game online-only was based in part on the success of ''Age of Empires II'' and the popularity of its online integration with [[MSN Gaming Zone]]. Since online player interaction through the game was made a priority by the studio, two iterations of the game had to be created; a server version and a client version. This resulted in a heavily modified version of the BANG engine used in previous games of the series, along with requiring large amounts of additional server code and infrastructure to be implemented. Excluding the tools, ''Age of Empires Online'' contains over 1.2 million lines of code.<ref name=\"Gamedesign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.robotentertainment.com/blog/detail/Brief-History-Time-And-Age-Engine|title=A Brief History of Time (And the Age Engine)|publisher=[[Robot Entertainment]]|date=September 10, 2010|accessdate=April 27, 2012|last=Fermier|first=Rob|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914080956/http://www.robotentertainment.com/blog/detail/Brief-History-Time-and-Age-Engine|archive-date=September 14, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn designing the new look for the game, Robot had six artists come together to create a new art style which would look similar to the previous games from the series, yet look more \"visually appealing\", \"timeless\", and \"bright\". Among the art team was Ensemble Studios' first artist Brad Crow, who had worked on every ''Age of Empires'' game produced by the studio. The team implemented several ideas to give the game an improved core visual interface over that of its predecessors such as; increasing the field of view so that the player was able to see more on the screen, a tighter user interface to allow more of the field of play to be visible, a new building design to make them encompass less screen space &mdash; while also making them look more recognizable, and giving each unit a unique look and animation making them more easily distinguishable from each other.<ref name=\"Artdesign\" />\n\nThe music and sound for the game was developed by GL33k and veteran video game composer [[Chris Rickwood]]. In composing the music, Rickwood strove to keep it in the spirit of [[Stephen Rippy|Stephen Rippy's]] and Kevin McMullan's work from the prior games of the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gl33k.com/consolepc/2011/8/15/age-of-empires-online.html |title=GL33k Game Audio - Console/PC - Age Of Empires Online |publisher=Gl33k.com |date=August 15, 2011 |accessdate=January 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130216041439/http://gl33k.com/consolepc/2011/8/15/age-of-empires-online.html |archive-date=February 16, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn February 24, 2011, it was announced - first via [[Chris Taylor (game designer)|Chris Taylor]]'s Facebook page - that [[Gas Powered Games]] had taken over development from Robot Entertainment. According to a blog post,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20110224|title=Blog post: Cooking with Gas.|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|date=February 24, 2011|accessdate=September 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120720121057/http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20110224|archive-date=July 20, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Gas Powered Games was already working on the game behind the scenes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/Articles/Announcements-2-24-2011.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725193026/http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/Articles/Announcements-2-24-2011.aspx|archivedate=July 25, 2011|title=Announcement: Gas Powered Games Joins Age Team|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|date=February 24, 2011|accessdate=September 6, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/2011/02/24/age-of-empires-online-swaps-devs|title=Age of Empires Online swaps devs|first=Dan|last=Stapleton|magazine=PC Gamer|date=February 24, 2011|accessdate=September 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902120027/http://www.pcgamer.com/2011/02/24/age-of-empires-online-swaps-devs/|archive-date=September 2, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> creating content packs and moving to take over as lead developers, which was planned for some time.  The game was released on August 16, 2011 with the Greek and Egyptian civilizations, followed by the Persians during the holiday. The Celts was postponed to March 2012, and was the first out of the four civilizations solely created from start to finish by Gas Powered Games since taking over development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120326|title=Blog Post: A Peek into AoEO Development: The Celts|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|date=March 26, 2012|accessdate=May 2, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329072649/http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120326|archive-date=March 29, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Support phase and official closure===\nOn January 3, 2013, it was announced by AOEO Trajan (Kevin Perry) via the official community blog that ''Age of Empires Online'' had finished its development stage and was entering its support phase,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20130103|title=Blog post: Future of Age of Empires Online.|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|date=January 3, 2013|accessdate=January 3, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106090932/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20130103|archive-date=January 6, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and in September 2013 Microsoft Studios announced that the Age of Empires Online servers would be shut down on July 1, 2014.<ref name=\"The Rest of AOEO\">{{cite web|url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20130916-1|title=The Rest of AOEO|publisher=Age of Empires Online Blog|date=September 16, 2013|access-date=November 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918200933/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20130916-1|archive-date=September 18, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Producer Kevin Perry gave a presentation at the 2013 [[Game Developers Conference]] explaining the reasons for AoEO's closure and why he believed its business model ultimately failed, that being mostly due to the content being too expensive to create for the small daily active userbase.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gdcvault.com/play/1019303/F2P-the-Wrong-Way-Age|title=GDC Vault - F2P the Wrong Way: Age of Empires Online|work=gdcvault.com|access-date=January 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320082107/http://www.gdcvault.com/play/1019303/F2P-the-Wrong-Way-Age|archive-date=March 20, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Project Celeste'' ===\n''Age of Empires Online'' has been republished in mid-2017 under a non-commercial license under Microsoft's \"Game Content Usage Rules\" by an independent group of developers and can be played for free on a [[server emulator]] known as ''Project Celeste'' with all online features fully enabled. The team uses Microsoft's publicly released development-kit to balance, fix bugs, and expand the content where Microsoft's team left off.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/projectceleste/wiki/faq#wiki_faq|title=faq - projectceleste|website=www.reddit.com|access-date=2019-01-13}}</ref>\n\n==Premium content==\nAt launch, the game offered ''premium content'' to players in the form of micro-transactions. As part of the game's launch on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] in March 2012, prices were lowered and Steam offered all premium content and booster packs in the game for a discount through the \"All in Wonder Bundle\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Sliwinski |first=Alexander |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2012/03/29/age-of-empires-online-hits-steam/ |title=Age of Empires Online hits Steam |publisher=Joystiq |date=March 29, 2012 |accessdate=May 8, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130914151427/http://www.joystiq.com/2012/03/29/age-of-empires-online-hits-steam/ |archive-date=September 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The developers later announced that in June 2012, the previous purchasing system would be discontinued, while all past and future premium content to be purchased through \"Empire points\" earned through gameplay. .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120423|title=Empire Points|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|date=April 23, 2012|accessdate=April 24, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425224740/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120423|archive-date=April 25, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 14, 2012 the summer patch went into place removing the original purchasing system for premium content and implemented the new \"Empire points\" system - making the game fully free to play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120531|title=Launch Date and Release Notes for the Summer Update|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|date=May 31, 2012|accessdate=June 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620024517/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120531|archive-date=June 20, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Booster packs===\n[[File:Aoeo skirmish.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Skirmish hall game setup screen. The Skirmish booster was added to fill an absent skirmish game-mode found in prior games of the series. Four player co-op support was later added as well.]]\nBooster packs allowed for the player to enjoy and experience very customizable PvE gameplay. The Defense of Crete booster pack was the first booster pack to be released for Age of Empires Online.\n\nThe Skirmish booster pack was the second booster pack to be released. The Skirmish booster pack adds allowed the player to choose every element of PvE gameplay<ref name=\"ageofempiresonline_a\">{{cite web|url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120110|title=Skirmish Hall|publisher=Microsoft|date=January 10, 2012|accessdate=April 27, 2012|last=Vogel|first=Ian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120423182148/http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120110|archive-date=April 23, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Vanity items===\nAt launch, there were several vanity packs for the game, These packs provided the player with blueprints to stores that allowed the player to purchase new items to use to customize and decorate their capital city with in-game gold.<ref>{{cite web |last=Vogel |first=Ian |url=https://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20110211 |title=Blog |publisher=Age of Empires Online |accessdate=January 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120720090843/http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20110211 |archive-date=July 20, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| title = Reception\n| GR = 71.09%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/605240-age-of-empires-online/index.html|title=Age of Empires Online for PC|publisher=[[GameRankings]]|accessdate=September 3, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810083752/http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/605240-age-of-empires-online/index.html|archive-date=August 10, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| MC = 70/100<ref name=\"MC\" />\n| 1UP = C+<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/reviews/age-empires-online-review|title=This is a Free-to-Read Age of Empires Online Review|first=Mike|last=Nelson|website=[[1UP.com]]|access-date=September 3, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160530203609/http://www.1up.com/reviews/age-empires-online-review|archive-date=May 30, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| Edge = 6/10<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.next-gen.biz/reviews/age-empires-online-review|title=Age Of Empires Online review|magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]|date=August 17, 2011|access-date=August 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228181542/http://www.next-gen.biz/reviews/age-empires-online-review|archive-date=December 28, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| EuroG = 7/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-08-17-age-of-empires-online-review|title=Age of Empires Online Review|first=Rich|last=Stanton|website=[[Eurogamer]]|date=August 17, 2011|access-date=August 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828193920/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-08-17-age-of-empires-online-review|archive-date=August 28, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 6.5/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/pc/strategy/age-of-empires-online/review.html|title=Age of Empires Online Review|first=Justin|last=Calvert|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=September 2, 2011|access-date=August 19, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924075529/http://www.gamespot.com/pc/strategy/age-of-empires-online/review.html|archive-date=September 24, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| IGN = 7.0/10<ref name=\"ignaoeo\" />\n| Joystiq = 7/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2011/08/16/age-of-empires-online-review/|title=Age of Empires Online review: Casual conquest|first=Jason|last=Dobson|publisher=Joystiq|date=August 16, 2011|access-date=August 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018203938/http://www.joystiq.com/2011/08/16/age-of-empires-online-review/|archive-date=October 18, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| PCGUK = 65/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/review/age-of-empires-online-review/|title=Age of Empires Online|work=PC Gamer|access-date=May 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519075052/http://www.pcgamer.com/review/age-of-empires-online-review/|archive-date=May 19, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| rev1 = Cheat Code Central\n| rev1Score = (4.2/5)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cheatcc.com/pc/rev/ageofempiresonlinereview2.html|title=Age of Empires Online Review for PC|first=Robert|last=VerBruggen|publisher=Cheat Code Central|access-date=August 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111229144932/http://www.cheatcc.com/pc/rev/ageofempiresonlinereview2.html|archive-date=December 29, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[GamesRadar|GamesRadar US]]\n| rev2Score = 6/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/pc/age-of-empires-online/review/age-of-empires-online-review/a-20110819161330135097/g-2011012617558984076|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130124101021/http://www.gamesradar.com/pc/age-of-empires-online/review/age-of-empires-online-review/a-20110819161330135097/g-2011012617558984076|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 24, 2013|title=Age of Empires Online review|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|publisher=[[GamesRadar|GamesRadar (US)]]|date=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev3 = MeriStation\n| rev3Score = 8/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meristation.com/v3/des_analisis.php?id=cw4e4938dd1a137&pic=PC&idj=cw4d3db51aaa3f6=|title=Age of Empires Online - An\u00e1lisis PC en MERISTATION|author=Jos\u00e9 \u00c1lvaro Sa\u00f1udo D\u00edaz|date=August 16, 2011|publisher=MeriStation|language=spanish}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Softonic.com]]''\n| rev4Score = 6/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pc.ongames.com/analisis_age-of-empires-online|title=Age of Empires Online, PC - an\u00e1lisis|first=Daniel|last=C\u00e1ceres|date=August 18, 2011|publisher=[[Softonic.com|OnGames (Softonic.com)]]|language=spanish|access-date=August 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130326111119/http://pc.ongames.com/analisis_age-of-empires-online|archive-date=March 26, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| rev5 = [[PC Magazine]]\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"PCMag\" />\n| rev6 = [[20 minutos|Vandal (20 minutos)]]\n| rev6Score = 8/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vandal.net/analisis/pc/age-of-empires-online/12895|title=An\u00e1lisis Age of Empires Online|first=Carlos|last=Leiva|date=August 16, 2011|publisher=[[20 minutos|Vandal (20 minutos)]]|language=spanish}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''Browsergamez''\n| rev7Score = 84/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://age-of-empires-online.browsergamez.com/tests/1537/1/age-of-empires-online-test-the-new-spin-on-an-old-classic-we-try-it-out.html|title=Age of Empires Online Test: The New Spin on an Old Classic \u2013 We Try It Out|work=Browsergamez.com|access-date=March 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116114409/http://age-of-empires-online.browsergamez.com/tests/1537/1/age-of-empires-online-test-the-new-spin-on-an-old-classic-we-try-it-out.html|archive-date=January 16, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Age of Empires Online'' received mixed reviews, garnering an aggregated review score of 70 on Metacritic.<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/age-of-empires-online|title=Age of Empires Online for PC|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=September 3, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904054146/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/age-of-empires-online|archive-date=September 4, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Some critics praise the co-operative missions, graphics, and familiar ''Age of Empires'' gameplay. However, many critics were critical of the price of the game's premium content.\n\nJustin Calvert of [[GameSpot]] gave the game a 6.5/10, noting the PvP matchmaking system, enemy AI, and pricing as weak points, but stated, \"''Age of Empires Online'' effectively infuses its conventional real-time strategy gameplay with massively multiplayer online-style loot and leveling mechanics.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/age-of-empires-online/reviews/age-of-empires-online-review-6332682/|title=Age of Empires Online Review|date=September 2, 2011|website=[[GameSpot]]|first=Justin|last=Calvert|accessdate=May 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501151231/http://www.gamespot.com/age-of-empires-online/reviews/age-of-empires-online-review-6332682/|archive-date=May 1, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[IGN]] gave the game a 7/10, with reviewer Nick Kolan critical of the game's best features being restricted to the premium content purchases. However, Kolan closed by saying, \"For all its flaws, I can\u2019t help but like ''Age of Empires Online''. Caught somewhere between massively-multiplayer online role-playing game and hardcore competitive real-time strategy, ''Age of Empires Online'' delivers some of the most addictive parts of both.\"<ref name=\"ignaoeo\">{{cite web|url=http://pc.ign.com/articles/119/1190293p1.html|title=Age of Empires Online Review|first=Nick|last=Kolan|website=IGN|date=August 24, 2011|accessdate=September 30, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928103243/http://pc.ign.com/articles/119/1190293p1.html|archive-date=September 28, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[PC Magazine]]'' gave the game 3.5 out of 5 stars, and complimented the in-game artwork as \"well done\" and \"nicely scalable\", but felt the free to play aspect should have offered more to the player. Reviewer Matthew Murray wrote, \"''Age of Empires Online'' is highly enjoyable, and I found myself afflicted with one-more-turn-itis when a fiendish mission objective captivated (or frustrated) me. That\u2019s not the case with every game I play\u2014and it\u2019s not nothing.\"<ref name=\"PCMag\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2391174,00.asp|title=Age of Empires Online Review & Rating|first=Matthew|last=Murray|magazine=[[PC Magazine]]|date=August 16, 2011|access-date=August 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909161140/https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2391174,00.asp|archive-date=September 9, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[GameSpy]] reviewer Mike Sharkey panned the game in his initial review,<ref name=\"Gamespy\">{{cite web|url=http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/robot-entertainment-project-1-untitled/1221468p1.html|title=Free Agent: Age of Empires Online|first=Mike|last=Sharkey|publisher=[[GameSpy]]|date=March 23, 2012|accessdate=March 31, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325190602/http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/robot-entertainment-project-1-untitled/1221468p1.html|archive-date=March 25, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> but after the game received a major overhaul patch he later stated, \"Well, AoE Online is now on [[Steam (software)|Steam]], and courtesy of a massive spring patch, the vast majority of the problems I had with it have been addressed.\"<ref name=\"Gamespy2\">{{cite web|url=http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/robot-entertainment-project-1-untitled/1221808p1.html|title=Age of Empires Online Launches on Steam|first=Mike|last=Sharkey|publisher=[[GameSpy]]|date=March 28, 2012|accessdate=March 31, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330230021/http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/robot-entertainment-project-1-untitled/1221808p1.html|archive-date=March 30, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[PC Gamer]]'' initially gave the game a 65/100 at launch,<ref name=\"PCGamer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/review/age-of-empires-online-review/|title=Age of Empires Online review|first=Tom|last=Senior|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=October 16, 2011|accessdate=May 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519075052/http://www.pcgamer.com/review/age-of-empires-online-review/|archive-date=May 19, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> but later reviewed the specific DLC Celts campaign giving it a score of 90/100 and calling it, \"The best free RTS gaming you'll find, the Celts bring AoEO two steps closer to greatness.\"<ref name=\"PCGamer2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/review/age-of-empires-online-premium-celtic-civilization/|title=Age of Empires Online: Premium Celtic Civilization|first=Josh|last=Augustine|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=May 8, 2012|accessdate=May 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510042813/http://www.pcgamer.com/review/age-of-empires-online-premium-celtic-civilization/|archive-date=May 10, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[PC Gamer]]'' later summarized the game's major complaints during its initial launch and noted that many of them were addressed or improved by the developers.<ref name=\"PCGamer3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/2012/07/04/did-age-of-empires-onlines-revamp-solve-its-biggest-problems/|title=Did Age of Empires Online\u2019s revamp solve its biggest problems?|first=Josh|last=Augustine|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=July 4, 2012|accessdate=January 31, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130209053603/http://www.pcgamer.com/2012/07/04/did-age-of-empires-onlines-revamp-solve-its-biggest-problems/|archive-date=February 9, 2013|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''Age of Empires Online'' was the third most played [[Games for Windows Live]] title for the year 2012 based on [[unique users]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2013/01/23/top-xbox-live-arcade-indie-and-windows-games-of-2012/|title=Top Xbox Live, Arcade, Indie and Windows games of 2012|work=Joystiq|access-date=January 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126101243/http://www.joystiq.com/2013/01/23/top-xbox-live-arcade-indie-and-windows-games-of-2012/|archive-date=January 26, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Upon its shutdown in 2014, ''Age of Empires Online'' had its players embark on 500 million single-player quests, another 13.7 million multiplayer quests, and 2 million arena matches in its three-year history.<ref name=shut/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20140606075858/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/}} (Archive)\n* [https://projectceleste.com ''Project Celeste''] (Unofficial server)\n*'' [https://www.bebee.com/producer/@ronald-ortega/doctor-strange-revivira-dos-personajes-en-el-multiverso-de-locura/ Pelis 24] about Age of Empires Online\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n{{Age of Empires series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2014}}\n\n[[Category:2011 video games]]\n[[Category:Age of Empires]]\n[[Category:Free-to-play video games]]\n[[Category:Games for Windows certified games]]\n[[Category:Inactive massively multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy games]]\n[[Category:Microsoft games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Real-time strategy video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games set in antiquity]]\n[[Category:Video games using Havok]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = Age of Empires Online\n|image = Age of Empire Online cover.jpg\n|caption =\n|developer = [[Robot Entertainment]]<br />[[Gas Powered Games]]\n|publisher = [[Microsoft Game Studios]]\n|designer =\n|series = ''[[Age of Empires]]''\n|engine = \n|platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n|released = {{Video game release|WW|August 16, 2011<ref name=\"ignrelease\">{{cite web|url=http://pc.ign.com/articles/117/1171807p1.html|title=Age of Empires Online Release Date|website=IGN|date=May 31, 2011|accessdate=September 30, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826023057/http://pc.ign.com/articles/117/1171807p1.html|archive-date=August 26, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>}}\n|genre = [[Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy game]]\n|modes = [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n}}\n'''''Age of Empires Online''''' was a [[multiplayer online real-time strategy game]] developed by [[Robot Entertainment]] and [[Gas Powered Games]], which released on August 16, 2011.<ref name=\"ignrelease\" /> Based upon the gameplay of the ''[[Age of Empires]]'' series, it was originally developed by [[Robot Entertainment]], but on February 24, 2011, [[Gas Powered Games]], took over production. The game was published by [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/press/2010/aug10/08-16msgamescompcpr.aspx|title=Microsoft Heralds a New Age of Gaming With \"Age of Empires Online\"|publisher=Microsoft website|date=August 16, 2010|accessdate=September 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120621112909/http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/press/2010/aug10/08-16MSGamescomPCPR.aspx|archive-date=June 21, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe game was [[free-to-play]]\u2014it was free for users to play, though premium content could be earned or purchased, such as access to special items and blueprints, and more quests and features.\n\nOn March 27, 2012, the game premiered on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] after a major overhaul patch which addressed complaints of an \"MMO-like grind\" and many other features, along with the debut of the [[Celts|Celtic]] civilization. On June 15, 2012 the premium content system was changed to offer the option to purchase all past and future content through \"Empire points\" earned in game, or by purchasing the points directly with real world money.\n\n{{As of|2013|1|3}}, [[Microsoft]] ceased further development on the game. A Microsoft representative later announced on the forums that on August 22, 2013, the [[Games for Windows \u2013 Live]] Marketplace would be shut down, leaving the game only accessible by current or former players.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forums.ageofempiresonline.com/forums/1/371493/ShowThread.aspx|title=Error|work=ageofempiresonline.com|access-date=August 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827132206/http://forums.ageofempiresonline.com/forums/1/371493/ShowThread.aspx|archive-date=August 27, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In September 2013, it was announced that the game would remain functional until July 1, 2014 when the service would be shut down.<ref>{{cite web|title=Age of Empires Online Shutdown Confirmed, Detailed|url=https://www.trueachievements.com/n14728/age-of-empires-online-shutdown-confirmed-detailed|website=True Achievements|access-date=August 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818215923/https://www.trueachievements.com/n14728/age-of-empires-online-shutdown-confirmed-detailed|archive-date=August 18, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The closure was due to the content being too expensive to maintain.<ref name=shut>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2013/8/19/4635640/age-of-empires-online-failure-to-be-profitable-due-to-its-lack-of|title=Age of Empires Online's lack of new content drove revenue loss|author=Corriea, Alexa Ray|website=Polygon|date=Aug 19, 2013|access-date=January 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612162928/https://www.polygon.com/2013/8/19/4635640/age-of-empires-online-failure-to-be-profitable-due-to-its-lack-of|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, ''Age of Empires Online'' was reestablished using Microsoft's publicly released developer-kit for the game and is now hosted on a [[server emulator]] known as ''Project Celeste''. The game can be played for free in single-player and multiplayer mode with all online features fully enabled.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://projectceleste.com/|title=Age of Empires Online \u2013 Celeste Fan Project|website=Age of Empires Online \u2013 Celeste Fan Project|language=en|access-date=2019-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930070719/https://www.projectceleste.com/|archive-date=September 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In May 2019, the team announced that they are developing Microsoft's unreleased Roman civilization for play based upon all known data of the civilization before the official servers were closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forums.projectceleste.com/threads/roman-civilization-announcement.4056/|title=Roman Civilization Announcement|website=Age Of Empires Online -- Celeste Fan Project}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Age of Empires Online Screenshot - Battle.png|thumb|left|300px|Gameplay screenshot showing a battle scene.]]\n''Age of Empires Online'', like its predecessors, is a real-time based strategy videogame. The game features much of the gameplay of [[Age of Empires|the series]], with the addition of a [[massively multiplayer online game|massive multiplayer online gaming]] element. The player possesses a capital city for each started civilization, that continues to exist when the player is offline. Also, the game features a great quantity of new content, such as the ability to craft items with earned materials and trading with other players.<ref name=\"features\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/features|title=General Features|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|accessdate=September 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920171542/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/features|archive-date=September 20, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe main gameplay revolved around the player developing a civilization from its birth to its peak and fall. To assure victory, the player had to gather and preserve resources to spend on new units, buildings and more advanced technology.\n\nCivilian units, called ''villagers'', were used to gather resources (hunting, fishing, farming, forestry, mining etc.).. Resources could be traded, and also \"spent\" to train units, construct buildings, and research technologies.\n\n===Units===\n''Age of Empires Online'' includes five classes of military units: Infantry, archers, cavalry, [[siege]] weaponry, and [[navy|naval]] units. All military classes are developed to maintain a balance on gameplay, and thus avoiding visible advantages between civilizations. As an example, a unit powerful against buildings can be weak against a certain kind of cavalry. Unique units are available for the Greek, Egyptian, Celts, and Persian civilizations, either from the start of the game or through advisor cards. These civilization-specific units are generally more powerful, but can still be vulnerable to certain units. The [[priest]] is a special kind of military unit that has the ability to convert enemy units to the player's civilization, and to heal allied units.<ref name=\"ageofempiresonline\">{{cite web |url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/features |title=Features |publisher=Age of Empires Online |accessdate=October 19, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018141503/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/features |archive-date=October 18, 2012 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nEvery player has a limit to the total number of units they can create\u2014a population limit\u2014but may not immediately use the entire potential population. The population limit increases with the number of houses or town centers in the player's village to a maximum of 200, with each house contributing five (or ten for the Norse) and each town center contributing 20 to the limit. There are two important features for unit management: The idle villager button, which helps players identify villagers that have not been assigned a task, and the town bell, which sends all of the player's villagers into the nearest town center, fortress or tower for safety.<ref name=\"ageofempiresonline\" />\n\n===Buildings===\nThe buildings in ''Age of Empires Online'' are either economic or military buildings. Buildings can research technologies and upgrades that increase economic, military or unit-based efficiency, as well as provide resources for the player. Each civilization has unique buildings, but some are common for all civilizations; the most important of these being the town center, where villagers are created, resources are stored, some technologies researched and in which the player can advance to the next age. The town center can fire arrows at enemy units within range. Other economic buildings available include the storehouse for resources, farms, docks (the dock may also produce several military ships), and houses to support a higher population.\n\nMilitary buildings include unit-producing buildings such as [[barracks]], archery ranges, stables, and fortresses, as well as defensive buildings such as walls and towers. Military buildings can perform research to improve the abilities of military units, increasing their strength, defensive capabilities, or other attributes. The fortress is a powerful defensive building which can train a variety of units, including the civilization's unique units, and fires arrows at enemy units within range. It can only be built after a player has reached the third age. There are two other important defensive buildings: Walls and towers. Walls are used to prevent access for enemy units to an enclosed area, while friendly units can traverse the walls through inserted gates. Towers are equipped with the ability to fire arrows at enemy units, or garrison friendly units for protection, and can be used in conjunction with walls in establishing defense lines. Watch posts are used for extendings the line of sight.\n\n===Capital city===\nThe capital city is similar to the \"Home city\" concept implemented in ''[[Age of Empires III]]''. The city functions as the player's home base for their civilization. It continues to exist even when the player logs out of the game, though it cannot be attacked or altered by other players. Through the capital city, the player can manage quests, improve technologies, send mail, craft items, participate in player to player trade, acquire and equip new gear for individual units, and visit other player's cities. Stores built within the city can be visited by other players and currency used for the items purchased will add to the player's funds. Unlike the home city from ''Age of Empires III'' where you can only customize the look of buildings, the capital city is completely customizable; buildings and rewards can be placed anywhere on the city map as the player chooses. Players can add buildings, rewards, houses as well as statues and bushes along with other things to decorate their capital city. \"Vanity Island\" exist to add new bushes and statues for the player to use to decorate their capital city. The city is also used as a gateway to other AI controlled cities within the region, where a player can visit and acquire new quests and items. The capital city also has many different buildings that the player can build. Craft schools, built from the city, produce gear and consumables for the player to use. Additionally, Microsoft released a crafting app for [[Windows Phone]] which a player can use to assist in crafting within the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.windowsphone.com/en-us/store/app/crafting-guide/bf135187-f944-4947-bf36-f94b8d46f6e4 |title=Crafting Guide &#124; Windows Phone Apps+Games Store (United States) |publisher=Windowsphone.com |accessdate=January 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111005149/http://www.windowsphone.com/en-us/store/app/crafting-guide/bf135187-f944-4947-bf36-f94b8d46f6e4 |archive-date=November 11, 2012 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Quests===\nQuests are the main [[PvE]] aspect of the game. Quests generally involve fighting and defeating the AI player. They are similar to the campaigns in previous ''[[Age of Empires]]'' games. They are completed when the objectives are met. Objectives in quests vary greatly, some quests involve defeating enemies, others involve protecting a building or unit, and some involve collecting a certain amount of resources while defending from the enemy. Quest rewards include experience points, gold, empire points, chests, and sometimes gear.  Certain quests also have a co-op option, which allows the player to do the quest with another player to help them. Certain quests also have an \"elite\" version, which allows for the player to gain a greater amount of rewards, but is more difficult presenting the player with a greater challenge.\n\nThe different civilizations also have different quest lines, e.g. the Celts have 80 unique quests that the other civilizations do not possess.<ref name=\"SpringPatchNotes\">{{cite web|url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120327|title=Blog post: Spring Patch notes|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|date=March 27, 2012|accessdate=September 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116155857/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120327|archive-date=November 16, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===PvP===\nPlayer versus player, or [[Player versus player|PvP]], is another aspect of the game. PvP in this game can be started in one of two ways: By using Sparta PvP to find a random match, or by using the arena in the capital city to play against a party member. Sparta PvP can be accessed by visiting the Sparta region in the world map. In Sparta PvP, there are two different types of PvP options. Standard PvP is the first option and allows the player to use star techs from their tech-tree as well as any gear and advisors that they have equipped in their capital city. This PvP option was first to be released. Champion mode PvP is the second Sparta PvP option. This is also sometimes known as ranked PvP while Standard PvP is known as unranked PvP. In this PvP option all gears, star techs and advisors are disabled and cannot be used to start the players off at an even footing. All gears equipped will provide the units with a cosmetic change but will not affect their stats like they would normally do in PvE missions.<ref name=\"features\" />\n\nIn Sparta PvP, the player starts off with a minimal amount of resources, a few villagers and their scout. Map selection is random and cannot be chosen by either players. Champion mode PvP results will also determine your [[TrueSkill]] ranking which is used to determine a player's rank globally as well as to help find the player a match and opponents for PvP. Currently, in Sparta PvP, there is an option for 1v1 PvP and 2v2 PvP. Rewards from Sparta PvP include experience points, empire points, gold and Sparta points which can be used in the stores in Sparta for chests, gear and consumables.\n\nPvP is also accessible through the Arena in the player's capital city. While identical to Sparta PvP in many ways, Arena PvP can differ in many ways. In Arena PvP, you can play against any human opponent in your party as well as choose the map and teams (if it is a 2v2 match) before starting the game. Arena PvP  will not affect your Sparta PvP Trueskill ranking. Finally, arena PvP also does not provide any rewards to the winning player. The August 2012 update also added a new spectator mode option for Arena PvP<ref name=\"AnniversaryUpdate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120814-2|title=Blog post: Anniversary Update - Design Notes|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|date=August 14, 2012|accessdate=September 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817225606/http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120814-2|archive-date=August 17, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the October 2012 update made Arena PvP (Standard or Champion mode) free for all players.<ref name=\"ageofempiresonline2\">{{cite web |author=GPG Design Team |url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20121022 |title=Blog |publisher=Age of Empires Online |date=October 22, 2012 |accessdate=January 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024231553/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20121022 |archive-date=October 24, 2012 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Civilizations===\nSix [[civilization]]s are available. Premium civilizations start at level 1 and are the Greeks, Egyptians, and Celts. Pro civilizations start at level 20 and are the Persians, Babylonians and the Norse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/civilizations|title=Civilizations|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|accessdate=September 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921002447/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/civilizations|archive-date=September 21, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Each civilization has technologies and units that are unique to them, so that no civilization possesses all the technologies or units possible within the game.\n\n==Development==\n[[File:AoEO-comparison1.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The developers intended for the game to be reminiscent of the previous games from the series, yet have a \"bold and more graphic look with a lot of character\".<ref name=\"Artdesign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.robotentertainment.com/blog/detail/Vision-behind-Age-Empires-Online|title=The Vision behind Age of Empires Online|publisher=[[Robot Entertainment]]|date=September 3, 2010|accessdate=April 27, 2012|last=Kubalak|first=David|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221011536/http://robotentertainment.com/blog/detail/Vision-behind-Age-Empires-Online|archive-date=February 21, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Note the near identical units and building placement.]]\n''Age of Empires Online'', under the working title ''Project S'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5582009/ex+age-of-empires-devs-working-on-microsoft-strategy-game |title=Ex-Age of Empires Devs Working On Microsoft StrategyGame |publisher=Kotaku |first=Luke |last=Plunkett |date=July 7, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818072443/http://kotaku.com/5582009/ex%2Bage-of-empires-devs-working-on-microsoft-strategy-game |archivedate=August 18, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> was to be the first game [[game development|developed]] by [[Robot Entertainment]], a company founded by 45 of the 110 former staff members of [[Ensemble Studios]], who created the ''[[Age of Empires]]'' series.<ref name=\"Robot\" /> The game was officially announced on August 16, 2010. Robot was hired by Microsoft to develop the game over a 24-month period. The entire studio team focused on it as their sole project, in an effort to earn startup funds for Robot's future projects.<ref name=\"Robot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/04/18/interview-patrick-hudson-robot-entertainment.aspx|title=Director's Cut: Interview With Robot Entertainment's Patrick Hudson|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=April 18, 2012|accessdate=April 30, 2012|first=Matt|last=Helgeson|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422063546/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/04/18/interview-patrick-hudson-robot-entertainment.aspx|archive-date=April 22, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring early production, ''Age of Empires Online'' was originally called ''Age of Empires IV''. The development team had noticed that many other RTS game developers had moved away from the \"economic game\". The team felt that ''[[Age of Empires II: The Age of Kings]]'' had blended the economic and military aspects of the game perfectly, so they decided to play test it with hindsight. They noticed that many features had been lost or changed over time. It was during this time the team decided to do an \"''Age of Kings'' style gameplay in an ''[[Age of Empires (video game)|Age of Empires]]'' setting\". The designers were surprised that fans of the series were most fond of the simpler aspects of the previous titles. Former ''Age of Empires II'' lead designer Ian M. Fischer stated, \"When we started floating some of the early [AoEO] out to people other pieces fell into place \u2013 I cannot tell you how many times I have had someone email me or talk to me at a show and mention how much they loved the villagers carrying big hunks of meat in the original Age or the priest \"wololo\"\". From that point on, one of the goals was to invoke nostalgia from fans of the series when playing the game, despite the newer and updated features.<ref name=\"Earlydesign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.robotentertainment.com/blog/detail/Hi-Honey-Were-Home|title=Hi Honey, We're Home|publisher=[[Robot Entertainment]]|date=August 27, 2010|accessdate=April 27, 2012|last=Fischer|first=Ian M.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301120444/http://www.robotentertainment.com/blog/detail/Hi-Honey-Were-Home|archive-date=March 1, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe decision to make the game online-only was based in part on the success of ''Age of Empires II'' and the popularity of its online integration with [[MSN Gaming Zone]]. Since online player interaction through the game was made a priority by the studio, two iterations of the game had to be created; a server version and a client version. This resulted in a heavily modified version of the BANG engine used in previous games of the series, along with requiring large amounts of additional server code and infrastructure to be implemented. Excluding the tools, ''Age of Empires Online'' contains over 1.2 million lines of code.<ref name=\"Gamedesign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.robotentertainment.com/blog/detail/Brief-History-Time-And-Age-Engine|title=A Brief History of Time (And the Age Engine)|publisher=[[Robot Entertainment]]|date=September 10, 2010|accessdate=April 27, 2012|last=Fermier|first=Rob|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914080956/http://www.robotentertainment.com/blog/detail/Brief-History-Time-and-Age-Engine|archive-date=September 14, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn designing the new look for the game, Robot had six artists come together to create a new art style which would look similar to the previous games from the series, yet look more \"visually appealing\", \"timeless\", and \"bright\". Among the art team was Ensemble Studios' first artist Brad Crow, who had worked on every ''Age of Empires'' game produced by the studio. The team implemented several ideas to give the game an improved core visual interface over that of its predecessors such as; increasing the field of view so that the player was able to see more on the screen, a tighter user interface to allow more of the field of play to be visible, a new building design to make them encompass less screen space &mdash; while also making them look more recognizable, and giving each unit a unique look and animation making them more easily distinguishable from each other.<ref name=\"Artdesign\" />\n\nThe music and sound for the game was developed by GL33k and veteran video game composer [[Chris Rickwood]]. In composing the music, Rickwood strove to keep it in the spirit of [[Stephen Rippy|Stephen Rippy's]] and Kevin McMullan's work from the prior games of the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gl33k.com/consolepc/2011/8/15/age-of-empires-online.html |title=GL33k Game Audio - Console/PC - Age Of Empires Online |publisher=Gl33k.com |date=August 15, 2011 |accessdate=January 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130216041439/http://gl33k.com/consolepc/2011/8/15/age-of-empires-online.html |archive-date=February 16, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn February 24, 2011, it was announced - first via [[Chris Taylor (game designer)|Chris Taylor]]'s Facebook page - that [[Gas Powered Games]] had taken over development from Robot Entertainment. According to a blog post,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20110224|title=Blog post: Cooking with Gas.|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|date=February 24, 2011|accessdate=September 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120720121057/http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20110224|archive-date=July 20, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Gas Powered Games was already working on the game behind the scenes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/Articles/Announcements-2-24-2011.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725193026/http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/Articles/Announcements-2-24-2011.aspx|archivedate=July 25, 2011|title=Announcement: Gas Powered Games Joins Age Team|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|date=February 24, 2011|accessdate=September 6, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/2011/02/24/age-of-empires-online-swaps-devs|title=Age of Empires Online swaps devs|first=Dan|last=Stapleton|magazine=PC Gamer|date=February 24, 2011|accessdate=September 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902120027/http://www.pcgamer.com/2011/02/24/age-of-empires-online-swaps-devs/|archive-date=September 2, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> creating content packs and moving to take over as lead developers, which was planned for some time.  The game was released on August 16, 2011 with the Greek and Egyptian civilizations, followed by the Persians during the holiday. The Celts was postponed to March 2012, and was the first out of the four civilizations solely created from start to finish by Gas Powered Games since taking over development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120326|title=Blog Post: A Peek into AoEO Development: The Celts|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|date=March 26, 2012|accessdate=May 2, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329072649/http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120326|archive-date=March 29, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Support phase and official closure===\nOn January 3, 2013, it was announced by AOEO Trajan (Kevin Perry) via the official community blog that ''Age of Empires Online'' had finished its development stage and was entering its support phase,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20130103|title=Blog post: Future of Age of Empires Online.|publisher=Age of Empires Online website|date=January 3, 2013|accessdate=January 3, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106090932/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20130103|archive-date=January 6, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and in September 2013 Microsoft Studios announced that the Age of Empires Online servers would be shut down on July 1, 2014.<ref name=\"The Rest of AOEO\">{{cite web|url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20130916-1|title=The Rest of AOEO|publisher=Age of Empires Online Blog|date=September 16, 2013|access-date=November 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918200933/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20130916-1|archive-date=September 18, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Producer Kevin Perry gave a presentation at the 2013 [[Game Developers Conference]] explaining the reasons for AoEO's closure and why he believed its business model ultimately failed, that being mostly due to the content being too expensive to create for the small daily active userbase.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gdcvault.com/play/1019303/F2P-the-Wrong-Way-Age|title=GDC Vault - F2P the Wrong Way: Age of Empires Online|work=gdcvault.com|access-date=January 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320082107/http://www.gdcvault.com/play/1019303/F2P-the-Wrong-Way-Age|archive-date=March 20, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Project Celeste'' ===\n''Age of Empires Online'' has been republished in mid-2017 under a non-commercial license under Microsoft's \"Game Content Usage Rules\" by an independent group of developers and can be played for free on a [[server emulator]] known as ''Project Celeste'' with all online features fully enabled. The team uses Microsoft's publicly released development-kit to balance, fix bugs, and expand the content where Microsoft's team left off.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/projectceleste/wiki/faq#wiki_faq|title=faq - projectceleste|website=www.reddit.com|access-date=2019-01-13}}</ref>\n\n==Premium content==\nAt launch, the game offered ''premium content'' to players in the form of micro-transactions. As part of the game's launch on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] in March 2012, prices were lowered and Steam offered all premium content and booster packs in the game for a discount through the \"All in Wonder Bundle\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Sliwinski |first=Alexander |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2012/03/29/age-of-empires-online-hits-steam/ |title=Age of Empires Online hits Steam |publisher=Joystiq |date=March 29, 2012 |accessdate=May 8, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130914151427/http://www.joystiq.com/2012/03/29/age-of-empires-online-hits-steam/ |archive-date=September 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The developers later announced that in June 2012, the previous purchasing system would be discontinued, while all past and future premium content to be purchased through \"Empire points\" earned through gameplay. .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120423|title=Empire Points|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|date=April 23, 2012|accessdate=April 24, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425224740/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120423|archive-date=April 25, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 14, 2012 the summer patch went into place removing the original purchasing system for premium content and implemented the new \"Empire points\" system - making the game fully free to play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120531|title=Launch Date and Release Notes for the Summer Update|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|date=May 31, 2012|accessdate=June 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620024517/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120531|archive-date=June 20, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Booster packs===\n[[File:Aoeo skirmish.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Skirmish hall game setup screen. The Skirmish booster was added to fill an absent skirmish game-mode found in prior games of the series. Four player co-op support was later added as well.]]\nBooster packs allowed for the player to enjoy and experience very customizable PvE gameplay. The Defense of Crete booster pack was the first booster pack to be released for Age of Empires Online.\n\nThe Skirmish booster pack was the second booster pack to be released. The Skirmish booster pack adds allowed the player to choose every element of PvE gameplay<ref name=\"ageofempiresonline_a\">{{cite web|url=http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120110|title=Skirmish Hall|publisher=Microsoft|date=January 10, 2012|accessdate=April 27, 2012|last=Vogel|first=Ian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120423182148/http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20120110|archive-date=April 23, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Vanity items===\nAt launch, there were several vanity packs for the game, These packs provided the player with blueprints to stores that allowed the player to purchase new items to use to customize and decorate their capital city with in-game gold.<ref>{{cite web |last=Vogel |first=Ian |url=https://ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20110211 |title=Blog |publisher=Age of Empires Online |accessdate=January 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120720090843/http://www.ageofempiresonline.com/en/articles/blog-20110211 |archive-date=July 20, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| title = Reception\n| GR = 71.09%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/605240-age-of-empires-online/index.html|title=Age of Empires Online for PC|publisher=[[GameRankings]]|accessdate=September 3, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810083752/http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/605240-age-of-empires-online/index.html|archive-date=August 10, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| MC = 70/100<ref name=\"MC\" />\n| 1UP = C+<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/reviews/age-empires-online-review|title=This is a Free-to-Read Age of Empires Online Review|first=Mike|last=Nelson|website=[[1UP.com]]|access-date=September 3, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160530203609/http://www.1up.com/reviews/age-empires-online-review|archive-date=May 30, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| Edge = 6/10<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.next-gen.biz/reviews/age-empires-online-review|title=Age Of Empires Online review|magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]|date=August 17, 2011|access-date=August 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228181542/http://www.next-gen.biz/reviews/age-empires-online-review|archive-date=December 28, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| EuroG = 7/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-08-17-age-of-empires-online-review|title=Age of Empires Online Review|first=Rich|last=Stanton|website=[[Eurogamer]]|date=August 17, 2011|access-date=August 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828193920/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-08-17-age-of-empires-online-review|archive-date=August 28, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 6.5/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/pc/strategy/age-of-empires-online/review.html|title=Age of Empires Online Review|first=Justin|last=Calvert|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=September 2, 2011|access-date=August 19, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924075529/http://www.gamespot.com/pc/strategy/age-of-empires-online/review.html|archive-date=September 24, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| IGN = 7.0/10<ref name=\"ignaoeo\" />\n| Joystiq = 7/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2011/08/16/age-of-empires-online-review/|title=Age of Empires Online review: Casual conquest|first=Jason|last=Dobson|publisher=Joystiq|date=August 16, 2011|access-date=August 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018203938/http://www.joystiq.com/2011/08/16/age-of-empires-online-review/|archive-date=October 18, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| PCGUK = 65/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/review/age-of-empires-online-review/|title=Age of Empires Online|work=PC Gamer|access-date=May 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519075052/http://www.pcgamer.com/review/age-of-empires-online-review/|archive-date=May 19, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| rev1 = Cheat Code Central\n| rev1Score = (4.2/5)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cheatcc.com/pc/rev/ageofempiresonlinereview2.html|title=Age of Empires Online Review for PC|first=Robert|last=VerBruggen|publisher=Cheat Code Central|access-date=August 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111229144932/http://www.cheatcc.com/pc/rev/ageofempiresonlinereview2.html|archive-date=December 29, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[GamesRadar|GamesRadar US]]\n| rev2Score = 6/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/pc/age-of-empires-online/review/age-of-empires-online-review/a-20110819161330135097/g-2011012617558984076|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130124101021/http://www.gamesradar.com/pc/age-of-empires-online/review/age-of-empires-online-review/a-20110819161330135097/g-2011012617558984076|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 24, 2013|title=Age of Empires Online review|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|publisher=[[GamesRadar|GamesRadar (US)]]|date=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev3 = MeriStation\n| rev3Score = 8/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meristation.com/v3/des_analisis.php?id=cw4e4938dd1a137&pic=PC&idj=cw4d3db51aaa3f6=|title=Age of Empires Online - An\u00e1lisis PC en MERISTATION|author=Jos\u00e9 \u00c1lvaro Sa\u00f1udo D\u00edaz|date=August 16, 2011|publisher=MeriStation|language=spanish}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Softonic.com]]''\n| rev4Score = 6/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pc.ongames.com/analisis_age-of-empires-online|title=Age of Empires Online, PC - an\u00e1lisis|first=Daniel|last=C\u00e1ceres|date=August 18, 2011|publisher=[[Softonic.com|OnGames (Softonic.com)]]|language=spanish|access-date=August 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130326111119/http://pc.ongames.com/analisis_age-of-empires-online|archive-date=March 26, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| rev5 = [[PC Magazine]]\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"PCMag\" />\n| rev6 = [[20 minutos|Vandal (20 minutos)]]\n| rev6Score = 8/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vandal.net/analisis/pc/age-of-empires-online/12895|title=An\u00e1lisis Age of Empires Online|first=Carlos|last=Leiva|date=August 16, 2011|publisher=[[20 minutos|Vandal (20 minutos)]]|language=spanish}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''Browsergamez''\n| rev7Score = 84/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://age-of-empires-online.browsergamez.com/tests/1537/1/age-of-empires-online-test-the-new-spin-on-an-old-classic-we-try-it-out.html|title=Age of Empires Online Test: The New Spin on an Old Classic \u2013 We Try It Out|work=Browsergamez.com|access-date=March 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116114409/http://age-of-empires-online.browsergamez.com/tests/1537/1/age-of-empires-online-test-the-new-spin-on-an-old-classic-we-try-it-out.html|archive-date=January 16, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Age of Empires Online'' received mixed reviews, garnering an aggregated review score of 70 on Metacritic.<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/age-of-empires-online|title=Age of Empires Online for PC|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=September 3, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904054146/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/age-of-empires-online|archive-date=September 4, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Some critics praise the co-operative missions, graphics, and familiar ''Age of Empires'' gameplay. However, many critics were critical of the price of the game's premium content.\n\nJustin Calvert of [[GameSpot]] gave the game a 6.5/10, noting the PvP matchmaking system, enemy AI, and pricing as weak points, but stated, \"''Age of Empires Online'' effectively infuses its conventional real-time strategy gameplay with massively multiplayer online-style loot and leveling mechanics.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/age-of-empires-online/reviews/age-of-empires-online-review-6332682/|title=Age of Empires Online Review|date=September 2, 2011|website=[[GameSpot]]|first=Justin|last=Calvert|accessdate=May 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501151231/http://www.gamespot.com/age-of-empires-online/reviews/age-of-empires-online-review-6332682/|archive-date=May 1, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[IGN]] gave the game a 7/10, with reviewer Nick Kolan critical of the game's best features being restricted to the premium content purchases. However, Kolan closed by saying, \"For all its flaws, I can\u2019t help but like ''Age of Empires Online''. Caught somewhere between massively-multiplayer online role-playing game and hardcore competitive real-time strategy, ''Age of Empires Online'' delivers some of the most addictive parts of both.\"<ref name=\"ignaoeo\">{{cite web|url=http://pc.ign.com/articles/119/1190293p1.html|title=Age of Empires Online Review|first=Nick|last=Kolan|website=IGN|date=August 24, 2011|accessdate=September 30, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928103243/http://pc.ign.com/articles/119/1190293p1.html|archive-date=September 28, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[PC Magazine]]'' gave the game 3.5 out of 5 stars, and complimented the in-game artwork as \"well done\" and \"nicely scalable\", but felt the free to play aspect should have offered more to the player. Reviewer Matthew Murray wrote, \"''Age of Empires Online'' is highly enjoyable, and I found myself afflicted with one-more-turn-itis when a fiendish mission objective captivated (or frustrated) me. That\u2019s not the case with every game I play\u2014and it\u2019s not nothing.\"<ref name=\"PCMag\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2391174,00.asp|title=Age of Empires Online Review & Rating|first=Matthew|last=Murray|magazine=[[PC Magazine]]|date=August 16, 2011|access-date=August 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909161140/https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2391174,00.asp|archive-date=September 9, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[GameSpy]] reviewer Mike Sharkey panned the game in his initial review,<ref name=\"Gamespy\">{{cite web|url=http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/robot-entertainment-project-1-untitled/1221468p1.html|title=Free Agent: Age of Empires Online|first=Mike|last=Sharkey|publisher=[[GameSpy]]|date=March 23, 2012|accessdate=March 31, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325190602/http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/robot-entertainment-project-1-untitled/1221468p1.html|archive-date=March 25, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> but after the game received a major overhaul patch he later stated, \"Well, AoE Online is now on [[Steam (software)|Steam]], and courtesy of a massive spring patch, the vast majority of the problems I had with it have been addressed.\"<ref name=\"Gamespy2\">{{cite web|url=http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/robot-entertainment-project-1-untitled/1221808p1.html|title=Age of Empires Online Launches on Steam|first=Mike|last=Sharkey|publisher=[[GameSpy]]|date=March 28, 2012|accessdate=March 31, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330230021/http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/robot-entertainment-project-1-untitled/1221808p1.html|archive-date=March 30, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[PC Gamer]]'' initially gave the game a 65/100 at launch,<ref name=\"PCGamer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/review/age-of-empires-online-review/|title=Age of Empires Online review|first=Tom|last=Senior|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=October 16, 2011|accessdate=May 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519075052/http://www.pcgamer.com/review/age-of-empires-online-review/|archive-date=May 19, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> but later reviewed the specific DLC Celts campaign giving it a score of 90/100 and calling it, \"The best free RTS gaming you'll find, the Celts bring AoEO two steps closer to greatness.\"<ref name=\"PCGamer2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/review/age-of-empires-online-premium-celtic-civilization/|title=Age of Empires Online: Premium Celtic Civilization|first=Josh|last=Augustine|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=May 8, 2012|accessdate=May 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510042813/http://www.pcgamer.com/review/age-of-empires-online-premium-celtic-civilization/|archive-date=May 10, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[PC Gamer]]'' later summarized the game's major complaints during its initial launch and noted that many of them were addressed or improved by the developers.<ref name=\"PCGamer3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/2012/07/04/did-age-of-empires-onlines-revamp-solve-its-biggest-problems/|title=Did Age of Empires Online\u2019s revamp solve its biggest problems?|first=Josh|last=Augustine|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=July 4, 2012|accessdate=January 31, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130209053603/http://www.pcgamer.com/2012/07/04/did-age-of-empires-onlines-revamp-solve-its-biggest-problems/|archive-date=February 9, 2013|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''Age of Empires Online'' was the third most played [[Games for Windows Live]] title for the year 2012 based on [[unique users]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2013/01/23/top-xbox-live-arcade-indie-and-windows-games-of-2012/|title=Top Xbox Live, Arcade, Indie and Windows games of 2012|work=Joystiq|access-date=January 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126101243/http://www.joystiq.com/2013/01/23/top-xbox-live-arcade-indie-and-windows-games-of-2012/|archive-date=January 26, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Upon its shutdown in 2014, ''Age of Empires Online'' had its players embark on 500 million single-player quests, another 13.7 million multiplayer quests, and 2 million arena matches in its three-year history.<ref name=shut/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20140606075858/http://ageofempiresonline.com/en/}} (Archive)\n* [https://projectceleste.com ''Project Celeste''] (Unofficial server)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n{{Age of Empires series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2014}}\n\n[[Category:2011 video games]]\n[[Category:Age of Empires]]\n[[Category:Free-to-play video games]]\n[[Category:Games for Windows certified games]]\n[[Category:Inactive massively multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy games]]\n[[Category:Microsoft games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer online games]